commit_message:
Miscellaneous (mostly test) cleanup

 * Always use testtools.TestCase, since we're relying on testtools
 * Always use mock (as opposed to unittest.mock) since we're relying on
   mock
 * Add note about when a missing logging handler was added
 * Stop %-formatting the giant usage string that doesn't actually need
   any formatting
 * Prefer assertIs, assertIn, assertIsInstance over assertTrue
 * Use else-self.fail instead of sentinel values
 * Check resp.get('error') is None before checking resp['success'] is
   True, so test failures actually tell you something useful
 * Tighten some isinstance assertions
 * Import MockHttpTest from correct location
 * Only populate clean_os_environ once
 * Use setUp for setup, not __init__
 * Replace assertIn(key, dict) and assertEqual(foo, dict[key]) with
   assertEqual(foo, dict.get(key)) when key is a literal and foo is not
   None
 * Use mock.patch.object instead of manually patching for tests
 * Use six.binary_type instead of type(''.encode('utf-8'))
 * Stop shadowing builtin bytes
 * Reclaim some margin
 * Stop checking the return-type of encode_utf8; we already know it's
   bytes

Change-Id: I2138ea553378ce88810b7353147c8645a8f8c90e

commit_message:
Process user iptables rules before INVALID

Process user-defined iptables rules before the INVALID DROP
rule. This is to allow scenarios where the VMs need to
legitimately receive packets that conntrack doesn't have an
entry for (e.g. SYN-ACK where the SYN wasn't sent by the VM).
A user can accomplish this by adding an allow rule that matches
the headers of these INVALID packets so they get permitted before
they hit the INVALID DROP rule.

Conflicts:
	neutron/agent/linux/iptables_firewall.py
	neutron/tests/unit/test_iptables_firewall.py
	neutron/tests/unit/test_security_groups_rpc.py

Closes-Bug: #1460741
Change-Id: Ie6ce5f3fa688f1bf25b77db5955211922d9fe85b

@Tim - well, that's up to the team I suppose. From personal experience, using eslint directly reduces the number of dependencies (see https://github.com/adametry/gulp-eslint/blob/master/package.json), and gives us precise control over which rules are active. Using the tool directly also makes consolidating linting style for openstack (see eslint-config-openstack) easier.

And, in the end, you should do exactly what infra does. And infra runs 'npm run lint'. What exactly runs behind that invocation is irrelevant, and I vote for less complexity."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-07 17:44:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

commit_message:
Switched from jshint to eslint

Both jshint and jslint contain the 'do no evil' license which
makes it unusable for OpenStack. This patch switches this project
to use eslint, the published eslint-config-openstack rules, and
the john-papa eslint style guides. It also adds the 'npm run lint'
command used by infra in the javascript-jobs macro.

Change-Id: I724d3a12fb5b9c85446adcd07c03a676e966bd41

commit_message:
Adding namespace for [drivers] section in oslo-config-generator

zaqar.conf.sample file can be generated by tox -e genconfig commnad.

The generated zaqar.conf.sample file is supposed to have a [drivers]
section as per zaqar README.rst
However, the [drivers] section is not present in zaqar.conf.sample file
This patch fixes it

Closes-bug: #1501130

Change-Id: Ic1d98680fe1040f68944b529b1c4c4ec2c835cea

[{'created': '2015-09-29 04:44:48.000000000', 'message': 'Fix order of arguments in assertEqual

Some tests used incorrect order assertEqual(observed, expected).
The correct order expected by testtools is
assertEqual(expected, observed).
This patch fix the issue in the module zaqar/tests/unit/common/ .

commit_message:
Fix order of arguments in assertEqual

Some tests used incorrect order assertEqual(observed, expected).

The correct order expected by testtools is
assertEqual(expected, observed).

This patch fix the issue in the module zaqar/tests/unit/common/ .
Partial-Bug: #1259292

Change-Id: Ia2272618593eee23d335efb2efce77f3556f6fca

commit_message:
Verify common server in Generic driver on startup

If we setup generic driver in DHSS=False mode, we need to provide
specific data for VM that will host shares and if we do not provide
such info or provide it incorrectly then we get error only trying
perform actions. But we should do validation on service start.

Change-Id: I325d6461c4b12f481769bb01f792ef850dba789c
Closes-Bug: #1502063

[{'created': '2015-10-07 19:19:54.000000000', 'message': 'Use power manager to reboot in agent deployments

This patch updates the reboot_and_finish_deploy function
for IPA based deployments so that we use the power manager
to send a proper REBOOT command to the instance after
trying to soft power off the client. This is important
for machines that use "external" power controllers which
may not know the power state of the host machine. In
such configurations users may rely on BIOS boot on power on
settings to active their machines. Simply sending a POWER_ON
in such configurations doesn't work because the machine is
already in a POWER_ON state (because it just deployed) so
nothing happens (the machined has power but isn't booted).

Change-Id: If5deddc1ecb069b68f2f1d766eb058691ca280af
Closes-bug: #1503839
'}]
commit_message:
Use power manager to reboot in agent deployments

This patch updates the reboot_and_finish_deploy function
for IPA based deployments so that we use the power manager
to send a proper REBOOT command to the instance after
trying to soft power off the client. This is important
for machines that use "external" power controllers which
may not know the power state of the host machine. In
such configurations users may rely on BIOS boot on power on
settings to active their machines. Simply sending a POWER_ON
in such configurations doesn't work because the machine is
already in a POWER_ON state (because it just deployed) so
nothing happens (the machined has power but isn't booted).

Change-Id: If5deddc1ecb069b68f2f1d766eb058691ca280af
Closes-bug: #1503839

commit_message:
Fixed multiple py34 gate issues

1. Scope mock of 'open' to module

By mocking 'open' at the module level, we can avoid affecting
'open' calls from other modules.

2. Stop using LOG.exception in contexts with no sys.exc_info set

Python 3.4 logger fills in record.exc_info with sys.exc_info() result
[1], and then it uses it to determine the current exception [2] to
append to the log message. Since there is no exception, exc_info[1] is
None, and we get AttributeError inside traceback module.

It's actually a bug in Python interpreter that it attempt to access the
attribute when there is no exception. It turns out that it's fixed in
latest master of cPython [3] (the intent of the patch does not seem
relevant, but it removes the offending code while reshuffling the code).
Note that now cPython correctly checks the exception value before
accessing its attributes [4].

The patch in cPython that resulted in the failure is [5] and is present
since initial Python 3k releases.

The patch in fixtures that broke us is [6].

[1]: https://hg.python.org/cpython/file/tip/Lib/logging/__init__.py#l1412
[2]: https://hg.python.org/cpython/file/tip/Lib/logging/__init__.py#l575
[3]: https://hg.python.org/cpython/rev/73afda5a4e4c
[4]: https://hg.python.org/cpython/rev/73afda5a4e4c#l6.484
[5]: https://hg.python.org/cpython/rev/2ee09afee126
[6]: https://github.com/testing-cabal/fixtures/commit/67dd2956943261e845a866dab155208c51da937e

Closes-Bug: #1503847
Closes-Bug: #1504053
Co-Authored-By: Ihar Hrachyshka <ihrachys@redhat.com>
Change-Id: I456b7846b8a53e4d3f8c91583685e0e1eaa84719

commit_message:
Only write to template files if template data changes

Currently the template data is assigned to the files dict regardless
of whether the data has changed or not.

This has no consequence on Liberty, but the files dict in Kilo
and Juno is a sqlalchemy MutableDict so these assignments are triggering
updates to the raw_template table. These updates are even triggered for
calls to heat resource-list. With large raw_template records this can make
heat unusable.

Therefore this fix is presented here as having no effect (and being
harmless) to git master, but high priority backports for Kilo and Juno.

Change-Id: Ibb714a9c5dc9f6879ff108419127da985a57897b
Closes-Bug: #1494108
(cherry-picked from 779ba8e431aecac3c451c08aedcc0ad8cf0a4449)

The part of a ResourceDefinition that lists explicit dependencies was not
round-trip stable. As a result, when we copied a new resource definition
into the existing template during a stack update, we would end up rewriting
the template unnecesarily (i.e. even though we check for changes) every

commit_message:
Make ResourceDefinition round-trip stable to avoid extra writes

The part of a ResourceDefinition that lists explicit dependencies was not
round-trip stable. As a result, when we copied a new resource definition
into the existing template during a stack update, we would end up rewriting
the template unnecesarily (i.e. even though we check for changes) every
time if depends_on was not specified in the resource originally. At the end
of each update, we write the new template to the DB in its entirety, which
removes these extra lines again, ensuring that we will experience the same
problem on every update. This was causing a *lot* of unnecessary writes.

This change ensures that the definition remains stable across a round-trip,
so that no unnecessary changes appear in the template.

Change-Id: If7292e49755db0153d7d0db9f7d3875fa9c1d408
Partial-Bug: #1494108
(cherry-picked from 9ebac709e2d3e8814fdee9de99ff49a4681b0ab2)

commit_message:
Fix traceback when generating output with no iterations

If a task is run with no successful iterations, the new failure mode
of MeanComputation throws an (uncaught) RallyException. This adds a
try-except to catch and handle it elegantly.

Change-Id: Ic1289052c1c7e1a27521a77371f825352c711148

commit_message:
Pull metrics by using TLS enabled client

Magnum introduced TLS support in swarm bay, so swarm monitor needs
to use TLS enabled client to pull data.

In addition, this commit eliminates data pulling from the docker
daemon of individual bay nodes, since they are not secured by TLS.
Instead, we always pull from swarm. Due to that, additional text
parsing is needed, since the output of docker.info from swarm is
not well formed.

Change-Id: I121bfa98622c240d5c777901794a35c0d8990345
Closes-Bug: #1503460

commit_message:
Correct shade keystone v2 job

The clouds.yaml file does not exist until devstack runs, so
we cannot edit it at this point. Instead, set an environment
variable that we can read in the shade post_test_hook script
and use it to modify the clouds.yaml file there.

Change-Id: Ibadf06f5426feabb3f7d198c24c4b5b2ea12eba0

commit_message:
Fix an occasional 400 error on functional gate

This error occurs on bay-delete. The cause is that heat sometimes
deleted the routerinterface resource before the deletion of its
associated floatingip resource. This commit adds a dependency to
avoid the incorrect order of deletion.

Change-Id: I099a68e65d70076b94a17103f57a8b09d7aaad88
Closes-Bug: #1504298

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-08-28 15:21:35.000000000', 'message': "Enable quote (double)

This enables the 'quote' rule to force the use of double quotes,
except in situations where escaping a doublequote is required.
Double quotes were chosen not because they have a syntactic benefit
(because in javascript they don't), but rather because the JSON
specification requires the use of doublequotes. Since JSON
is frequently used in javascript projects, it makes sense to keep
everything consistent.

http://eslint.org/docs/rules/quotes

Change-Id: Ic57e5931a67a5fdc8f6a72144b44ca41939ea565
"}, {'created': '2015-09-01 23:49:05.000000000', 'message': 'Disable quote

Removes TODO comment from the `quote` rule. There is no functional
difference between using any of the quoting options. Individual
projects may choose to enable this rule on their own.

http://eslint.org/docs/rules/quotes

Change-Id: Ic57e5931a67a5fdc8f6a72144b44ca41939ea565
'}, {'created': '2015-09-22 17:25:30.000000000', 'message': 'Disable quote

Removes TODO comment from the `quote` rule. There is no functional
difference between using any of the quoting options. Individual
projects may choose to enable this rule on their own.

http://eslint.org/docs/rules/quotes

Change-Id: Ic57e5931a67a5fdc8f6a72144b44ca41939ea565
'}]
commit_message:
Disable quote

Removes TODO comment from the `quote` rule. There is no functional
difference between using any of the quoting options. Individual
projects may choose to enable this rule on their own.

http://eslint.org/docs/rules/quotes

Change-Id: Ic57e5931a67a5fdc8f6a72144b44ca41939ea565

commit_message:
Enable no-use-before-define

Disallow Early Use (no-use-before-define)

In JavaScript, prior to ES6, variable and function declarations are
hoisted to the top of a scope, so it's possible to use identifiers
before their formal declarations in code. This can be confusing and
some believe it is best to always declare variables and functions
before using them.

In ES6, block-level bindings (let and const) introduce a "temporal
dead zone" where a ReferenceError will be thrown with any attempt to
access the variable before its declaration.

http://eslint.org/docs/rules/no-use-before-define

Change-Id: Ia905b77e0938ac3e0279712bc6e5ccdb18a102e7

commit_message:
Add TLS support in heat kubernetes

This patch modifies template to generate certificates and configure TLS
settings for kube-apiserver/kubelet/kube-proxy.

Co-Authored-By: Andrew Melton <andrew.melton@rackspace.com>
Partially-Implements: bp secure-kubernetes
Change-Id: I76b0f91f0c44f9880980e35c6b8856ea48ed3ce1

commit_message:
Try to use zuul-cloner to prepare fixtures

In OpenStack Infra, we would like to run Puppet unit tests that
sometimes depends on other Puppet OpenStack modules.
Example: a patch in puppet-openstacklib that needs to be tested in puppet-nova.

This patch modifies the Rakefile to:
* clean spec_prep and spec_clean Rake tasks
* use openstack/puppet-openstack-integration/install_modules_unit.sh script
  to clone modules.
* do not use .fixtures.yaml file to clone modules and rely on
  zuul-cloner or git.
* Add openstack/ in gitignore so we never commit the
  puppet-openstack-integration repository (can happen when spec_clean
  did not run but you want to submit the patch anyway)
* Allow to run a custom Puppetfile if PUPPETFILE env is exported. It
  will allow people to test the module with the dependencies they like,
  feature we had with .fixtures.yaml.

Also add 'r10k' to Gemfile.

That way, we will be able to use zuul dependencies and run tests accross
modules like we do with functional testing.

Change-Id: I50a431558df8bad5c03c42921fcc7fc0fa51bb3d

commit_message:
Activate pep8 check that _ is imported

Remove the specification in tox.ini that _ is a builtin so that
it will no longer assume that _ does not need to be imported.
This helps ensure that the _ from i18n is used.

Activating this check did flag violations and they were fixed
in this patch.

Change-Id: Ia7e4c75b2126a67784683d1c22f0e24bc44113a4

commit_message:
Need to populate is_admin in context from policy

Context from the request was not getting popoulated with the is_admin
attribute, as we did not need this so far. Populating the same by
encforcing the policy.

'magnum-service:get_all' depends on 'rule:admin_api', which was getting
blocked due to policy enforcement.

Artifacts:
 - magnum/keystone code swaps the client depending on is_admin, which
   causes baymodel creation failures. Hence, removing the code, unless
   we need it.

Change-Id: I9a81a9962e5df62d9f67834493f554c6b4e5107d
Closes-Bug: #1503402

commit_message:
No need for Oslo Incubator Sync

We can remove openstack-common.conf as we don't
sync any code from oslo-incubator any more.

Change-Id: I5534debcaa10c1ac2292aa23631ff7136d091c98

commit_message:
Fix InstanceV1 backports to use context

This fixes the InstanceV1 and InstanceListV1 backport code to properly
initialize the temporary objects with a context. Without them, the
objects are orphaned and can't do certain things.

This should be backported to liberty

Closes-Bug: #1503708
Change-Id: I537734c0f10110ac64799cc1232edbc18a16c794

commit_message:
Remove unused service catalog module

We now use the Keystone client itself to work with the keystone service
catalog, and nothing is currently using this module, so safe to remove.

Change-Id: I7aa6e6166ae694624d3ca3deab6df0527da5f612

subject: Removed --name from cinder list as there was no NAME column in cinder volumes database.

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Gerrit_Workflow
    Commit Messages: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages"}, {'account_id': 11600, 'date': '2015-01-08 13:31:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Actually API allows name instead of display_name. See this snippet: https://github.com/openstack/cinder/blob/master/cinder/api/v2/volumes.py#L228-L231'}, {'account_id': 10559, 'date': '2015-01-08 13:57:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Add filtering snapshots by tenant ID

Cinder API supports to list volumes by tenant-id.
However, snapshots doesn't. This commit add tenant
option to snapshot-list option.

Change-Id: I2a71b5ead16971ed2cbfe0e2fc2b539324d50b60
Depends-On: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/166689
Closed-Bug: #1435110

commit_message:
Service representation using binary attribute

This patch fixes the exception thrown when trying to print
a service by using the binary attribute instead of the non
existing attribute service that is causing the exception.
Adding also a test case that reproduces the bug without
this patch.

Change-Id: I0684313292b6caa890e8267570e128abacc1550e
Closes-Bug: #1333947

commit_message:
Make backup-list support all-tenants options

Cinder backup-list doesn't support --all-tenants
option which has supported by volume and snapshot
list. This commit realizes it.

Change-Id: Ia14f4a0ad1043f75a2bf1aa402a18ed63eb85c5c
Depends-On: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/166727/
Closes-Bug: #1435158

commit_message:
No need for Oslo Incubator Sync

We can remove openstack-common.conf as we don't
sync any code from oslo-incubator any more.

commit_message:
Update Service.__repr__ to use 'binary' and 'host' fields

Address an issue where the __repr__ method for v1 and v2 versions of
service.list() throw an uncaught AttributeError when looking for the
'service' attribute.  This update uses the 'binary' and 'host'
attributes which contains a reasonable representation.

Closes-Bug: #1315606
Change-Id: I0e4dafde7152e2376491808becef7243f391545a

lgtm, agree with Michal about default available state, different behavior here will be confusing.'}, {'account_id': 9003, 'date': '2015-04-08 12:25:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12: Code-Review-1

With regard to the consistency with volume and snapshot
reset-state, see the discussion about the dangers of reset-state from the last mid-cycle meetup:

https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/cinder-meetup-winter-2015

For failed backup-create we really need a forced-delete.
Setting the backup to available without doing a delete as
followup is dangerous as it creates the illusion that restore would work.

For a failed restore I can see the value of setting the
backup state back to available but having this as the
default, even for failed backup-creates, still seems
dangerous.'}, {'account_id': 7173, 'date': '2015-04-08 17:16:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12: Code-Review-1

The consensus from the mid-cycle meetup regarding reset-state was that it was dangerous and would be deprecated once a more thorough solution was in place. I don't think that setting the state to 'available' is justified by keeping it consistent with the already broken reset-state for volumes.
The link for the blueprint seems broken, but I found the spec link in earlier patch ... The spec states:

"If we have reset-state API and resetting status from creating to available, we first verify whether the backup is ok on storage backend. If so, we change backup status from creating to available.If not, we throw an exception and change backup status from creating to error."

But I don't see that functionality in the patch that is submitted here. There is nothing to verify the backup on the storage backend. It is incomplete to just fix the database and not deal with whether or not a backup has been created.'}, {'account_id': 1207, 'date': '2015-04-08 17:34:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12: Code-Review+1

scottda: The server side of this (which I think is already merged) does the check to see if the backup is good (called verify in the backup driver, if the driver provides that function.'}, {'account_id': 7173, 'date': '2015-04-08 17:39:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12: -Code-Review

commit_message:
Add reset-state function for backups

Since there are volume reset-state function and snapshot reset-state
function, backup also needs reset-state as well.

When creating or restoring backup, it may leave the backup stuck in
creating or restoring status due to database or RabbitMQ failure.
Currently we could only solve these problems by restarting cinder-backup
service.

This change is to provide another means for administrators to solve
these problems by calling backup reset state API, instead of directly
restarting cinder-backup service.

blueprint support-reset-state-for-backup
DocImpact
Co-Authored-By: Michal Dulko <michal.dulko@intel.com>
Change-Id: I0093a34f0bf0745be5f63995f73ccdda7d561d52

[{'created': '2014-07-10 17:03:26.000000000', 'message': "Updates help and error handling for --all-tenants sub command

 * Documents that the environment variable ALL_TENANTS can be
   used as a default for the list command's --all-tenants flag
   for both volume list and snapshot list in the v1 and v2
   cinderclients.
 * When recieving improper input, raises a ValueError
   with a more helpful message, instead of int()'s base10 error
   message.

Change-Id: I709fba10b6a5bd8f88f4f6f6f537a5762de737fc
"}]
commit_message:
Updates help and error handling for --all-tenants sub command

 * Documents that the environment variable ALL_TENANTS can be
   used as a default for the list command's --all-tenants flag
   for both volume list and snapshot list in the v1 and v2
   cinderclients.
 * When recieving improper input, raises a ValueError
   with a more helpful message, instead of int()'s base10 error
   message.

Change-Id: I709fba10b6a5bd8f88f4f6f6f537a5762de737fc

commit_message:
Support filtering volumes by tenantId

Cinder API has supported filtering volumes
by tenant id for admin. However, cinderclient
doesn't support it. This commit realizes it.

Change-Id: I81c64dede8da94bb500a9a8d299431d55bcfa333
Closes-Bug: #1434973

commit_message:
Allow manually specified auth token

cinderclient will grab a token/service URL from keystone each time it
is used. The bypass-url option allows the API endpoint to be overridden
but there is no equivalent for the token.

This patch allows the token to be specified so it can be cached and
managed separately from the client.

Change-Id: If103f5a90b943e97a427b2a3d84cf1b7eec3f7c0
Closes-Bug: #1197746

commit_message:
Make cinderclient support snapshot-force-delete

Cinderclient doesn't support snapshot-force-delete, which
has supported by cinder-api, so add it to cinderclient.

Change-Id: Ia0280c24f4b9978da3af88ceb3fe556a82792c10
Closes-Bug: #1418353

At the midcycle meetup, we've decided not to add more reset-state APIs, but instead implement force operations to correct the problem when Cinder db and backend are out of sync. Scott is working on this."}, {'account_id': 7173, 'date': '2015-02-09 23:37:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I'd like to look at the blueprint for this, to see what you are trying to achieve.
The problem with reset-state is that it only affects the Cinder DB, without regard to what is actually happening with the volume. For migrating, this could be especially problematic, since the volume might be already migrated, or still on the original backend, and setting the DB state might render the volume inaccessible.
But I'm not sure that my changes to allow force_detach or force_attach will fix things during migration. That will likely require an entirely new API(s) i.e. force_migrate_back/force_migrate or something like that."}, {'account_id': 2861, 'date': '2015-06-18 07:30:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

[{'created': '2014-10-14 08:22:15.000000000', 'message': 'Allow reset-state on attach and migration fields

This modification adds support for reseting attach status and migration
status of volume.

usage of the commands:
usage: cinder reset-state [--state <state>] [--attach-status
<attach_status>] [--migration-status <migration_status>] <volume>
[<volume> ...]

Explicitly updates the volume state.

Positional arguments:
  <volume>         Name or ID of volume to modify.

Optional arguments:
  --state <state>  The state to assign to the volume. Valid values are
  "available," "error," "creating," "deleting," and "error_deleting."
  Default=available.
  --attach-status <attach_status>  The attach status to assign to the
  volume. Valid values are "attached", "detached". Default=None.
  --migration-status <migration_status>  The migration status to assign to
  the volume. Valid values are "migrating", "starting", "completing",
  "error", and "none". Default=None.

This modification is based on the patch:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/88083/

commit_message:
Allow reset-state on attach and migration fields

This modification adds support for reseting attach status and migration
status of volume.

usage of the commands:
usage: cinder reset-state [--state <state>] [--attach-status
<attach_status>] [--migration-status <migration_status>] <volume>
[<volume> ...]

Explicitly updates the volume state.

Positional arguments:
  <volume>         Name or ID of volume to modify.

Optional arguments:
  --state <state>  The state to assign to the volume. Valid values are
  "available," "error," "creating," "deleting," and "error_deleting."
  Default=available.
  --attach-status <attach_status>  The attach status to assign to the
  volume. Valid values are "attached", "detached". Default=None.
  --migration-status <migration_status>  The migration status to assign to
  the volume. Valid values are "migrating", "starting", "completing",
  "error", and "none". Default=None.

This modification is based on the patch:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/88083/

DocImpact

commit_message:
Fix bypass_url option, required by session object

A bypass_url option has been added to the client in commit
7a50182fbee06d7481bf7467c2ef82c54e9fe4d1. This allows the service
endpoint to be specified manually instead of being retrieved from the
catalogue.

For this to work when the cinderclient binary is being used the
bypass_url must be supplied to the session object that is created. The
SessionClient class takes the kwarg endpoint_override, this is
equivalent to the bypass_url. Nova is currently supplying the
endpoint_override as a kwarg when it creates a cinder client object.

This commit updates the naming of bypass_url to endpoint_override where
it is used internally in cinderclient and the kwargs supplied to the
session object created by the shell to include the bypass_url.

Change-Id: I405503d8df386b4235518206379c89064907ee5a
Closes-Bug: #1350702

commit_message:
add cinder type-show cmd

in python-cinderclient, we can use cinder type-list to show all
volume type, but when we want to show a specified volume type,
we found no client command, so add it. we can use it like this:
cinder type-show volume-type-id-or-name

Change-Id: Ib1f5d111c1dd62eac3d370c814c7ca43faaa029f

commit_message:
Return tuple containing header and body from client

Return tuple containing header and body from all
cinder-client api's instead of just body.

This change enables callers to get cinder's request IDs
('x-openstack-request-id' in the response header).
Therefore callers can log the mappings of request IDs
between cinder and callers.

Change-Id: I20fae76c9959bec2136bcee4a87d696c9ff52d4c
blueprint: return-req-id

commit_message:
Install ironicclient after installing the shade library

Shade needs to be installed before ironicclient, as ironicclient is a
dependency, pip ends up removing the previously installed version when
we force the upgrade operation, which may downgrade the library to the
released version which may be undesirable.

Additionally set the pip install of ironicclient to be latest instead
of being present.

Depends-On: I23e902c8637e142fba23d71467225d48ee265253
Change-Id: I3b1dca09e95e7a29b9f7e4b0a048aaa46bb2e22e

I don't understand the point of this. We have unit tests, and those tests should be restricted to the local repository.

What we're doing with beaker is an integration test, so it makes sense to consider other repositories.

Beaker is relatively new and everyone does it a bit differently so running our tests in an odd way is fine. But rspec-puppet has some really well established use patterns that we should not dump lightly."}, {'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2015-09-30 16:22:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 24:

@Spencer:

Please have a look at the patch's background [1].

Here are some facts:
* unit tests are not run against the same dependencies as functional tests
* unit tests are not using the same dependencies (fixtures.yaml is not consistent across all modules)
* because we use fixtures, our patches can't use Depends-On zuul feature for unit tests

My proposal is about:
* using a single place (Puppetfile) to define our dependencies.
* use this Puppetfile for both functional & unit testing.
* Allow people to change Puppetfile locally (see commit message) and patch history.
* Allow people to not run zuul on their laptop. Instead of zuul-cloner, it will just use git (and not fixtures anymore).

Please extend your concern, and maybe propose a better solution.

Thanks

[1] http://osdir.com/ml/openstack-dev/2015-09/msg01909.html"}, {'account_id': 7423, 'date': '2015-09-30 16:35:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 24: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 6554, 'date': '2015-09-30 17:47:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 24:

Emilien,

Why do unit tests need depends-on? If they are affected by other modules then we aren't doing 'unit tests' very well.

Again, the pattern for beaker isn't there yet in the community so we can do whatever. The pattern for rspec-puppet is there so going off into the woods on our own makes it harder for new contributors and for us to consume best practices from the community."}, {'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2015-09-30 18:17:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 24:

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-09-23 14:38:05.000000000', 'message': "Try to use zuul-cloner to prepare fixtures

In OpenStack Infra, we would like to run Puppet unit tests that
sometimes depends on other Puppet OpenStack modules.
Example: a patch in puppet-openstacklib that needs to be tested in puppet-nova.

If /usr/zuul-env/bin/zuul-cloner is present on the machine where tests
run, this patch modifies the Rakefile to:
* clean spec_prep and spec_clean Rake tasks
* use openstack/puppet-openstack-integration/isntall_modules.sh script
  to clone modules, like it's done with Beaker.
* do not use .fixtures.yaml file to clone modules and rely on
  zuul-cloner.

That way, we will be able to use zuul dependencies and run tests accross
modules like we do with functional testing.

Change-Id: Id33c964252cbd1fa1e1b2d06ae946da7fca9bcf5
Depends-On: Ie32d18d477c271b2724290edbbfd4ae7ea110480

If /usr/zuul-env/bin/zuul-cloner is present on the machine where tests
run, this patch modifies the Rakefile to:
* clean spec_prep and spec_clean Rake tasks
* use openstack/puppet-openstack-integration/isntall_modules.sh script
  to clone modules, like it's done with Beaker.
* do not use .fixtures.yaml file to clone modules and rely on
  zuul-cloner.

Also add 'r10k' to Gemfile.

That way, we will be able to use zuul dependencies and run tests accross
modules like we do with functional testing.

Depends-On: Ie32d18d477c271b2724290edbbfd4ae7ea110480
Change-Id: Id33c964252cbd1fa1e1b2d06ae946da7fca9bcf5

In OpenStack Infra, we would like to run Puppet unit tests that

This patch modifies the Rakefile to:
* clean spec_prep and spec_clean Rake tasks
* use openstack/puppet-openstack-integration/install_modules.sh script

  zuul-cloner or git.
* Add openstack/ in gitignore so we never commit the
  puppet-openstack-integration repository (can happen when spec_clean
  did nor run but you want to submit the patch anyway)
* Allow to run a custom Puppetfile if PUPPETFILE env is exported. It
  will allow people to test the module with the dependencies they like,
  feature we had with .fixtures.yaml.

Also add 'r10k' to Gemfile.

That way, we will be able to use zuul dependencies and run tests accross
modules like we do with functional testing.

commit_message:
Try to use zuul-cloner to prepare fixtures

In OpenStack Infra, we would like to run Puppet unit tests that
sometimes depends on other Puppet OpenStack modules.
Example: a patch in puppet-openstacklib that needs to be tested in puppet-nova.

This patch modifies the Rakefile to:
* clean spec_prep and spec_clean Rake tasks
* use openstack/puppet-openstack-integration/install_modules_unit.sh script
  to clone modules.
* do not use .fixtures.yaml file to clone modules and rely on
  zuul-cloner or git.
* Add openstack/ in gitignore so we never commit the
  puppet-openstack-integration repository (can happen when spec_clean
  did not run but you want to submit the patch anyway)
* Allow to run a custom Puppetfile if PUPPETFILE env is exported. It
  will allow people to test the module with the dependencies they like,
  feature we had with .fixtures.yaml.

Also add 'r10k' to Gemfile.

That way, we will be able to use zuul dependencies and run tests accross
modules like we do with functional testing.

Change-Id: Id33c964252cbd1fa1e1b2d06ae946da7fca9bcf5

commit_message:
Move most of green helper classes -> '_green.py'

Instead of having the green executor(s) helper classes
be inline with the rest of the other executors move its
helper classes/objects into its own module and use them
from there instead.

This also moves the work item helper into '_utils.py' for
similar/equivalent reasons.

Change-Id: I028738bf7d64f97320450d63debbd5116b505a72

commit_message:
Only write to template files if template data changes

Currently the template data is assigned to the files dict regardless
of whether the data has changed or not.

This has no consequence on Liberty, but the files dict in Kilo
and Juno is a sqlalchemy MutableDict so these assignments are triggering
updates to the raw_template table. These updates are even triggered for
calls to heat resource-list. With large raw_template records this can make
heat unusable.

Therefore this fix is presented here as having no effect (and being
harmless) to git master, but high priority backports for Kilo and Juno.

Change-Id: Ibb714a9c5dc9f6879ff108419127da985a57897b
Closes-Bug: #1494108
(cherry picked from commit 779ba8e431aecac3c451c08aedcc0ad8cf0a4449)

The part of a ResourceDefinition that lists explicit dependencies was not
round-trip stable. As a result, when we copied a new resource definition
into the existing template during a stack update, we would end up rewriting
the template unnecesarily (i.e. even though we check for changes) every

commit_message:
Make ResourceDefinition round-trip stable to avoid extra writes

The part of a ResourceDefinition that lists explicit dependencies was not
round-trip stable. As a result, when we copied a new resource definition
into the existing template during a stack update, we would end up rewriting
the template unnecesarily (i.e. even though we check for changes) every
time if depends_on was not specified in the resource originally. At the end
of each update, we write the new template to the DB in its entirety, which
removes these extra lines again, ensuring that we will experience the same
problem on every update. This was causing a *lot* of unnecessary writes.

This change ensures that the definition remains stable across a round-trip,
so that no unnecessary changes appear in the template.

Change-Id: If7292e49755db0153d7d0db9f7d3875fa9c1d408
Partial-Bug: #1494108
(cherry picked from commit a69431ab6c938ce591082344f0bebc30ef9464eb)

commit_message:
Fix bad exception for StrOpt with invalid choice value

If there's a StrOpt with name foo and say choices ['bar', 'baz'] and the
config file has a bad value for foo (say 'boo'), then the end user
will see:
NoSuchOptError: no such option: foo

Which gives the wrong impression that somehow the foo was never registered
which is wrong!

They should see this instead:
oslo_config.cfg.ConfigFileValueError: Value for option foo is not
valid: Valid values are [bar, baz], but found 'boo'

Closes-Bug: #1499074
Change-Id: I694d8aa99c861c7b47bae77ef12f435b7c3712ab

[{'created': '2015-10-05 20:19:15.000000000', 'message': "RetryDecorator should not log warnings/errors for expected exceptions

The RetryDecorator is constructed with a list of expected exceptions and
if the function being retried raises an exception in that list, it is
currently logging a warning (with traceback). If there is a timeout, an
error is also logged.

This is bad practice because only the caller of the method being retried
has context as to what's going on and knows what level things should be
logged at (and if tracebacks should be logged at all).

This change drops the warning and error logging to debug level. We let
the caller handle the final re-raised exception and handle logging it at
the appropriate level and with the appropriate context for the message
to make sense to someone reading the logs rather than the somewhat
obscure messages logged within RetryDecorator.

commit_message:
RetryDecorator should not log warnings/errors for expected exceptions

The RetryDecorator is constructed with a list of expected exceptions and
if the function being retried raises an exception in that list, it is
currently logging a warning (with traceback). If there is a timeout, an
error is also logged.

This is bad practice because only the caller of the method being retried
has context as to what's going on and knows what level things should be
logged at (and if tracebacks should be logged at all).

This change drops the warning and error logging to debug level. We let
the caller handle the final re-raised exception and handle logging it at
the appropriate level and with the appropriate context for the message
to make sense to someone reading the logs rather than the somewhat
obscure messages logged within RetryDecorator.

Closes-Bug: #1503017

Change-Id: I07344aae977aca540a0555eef8d35b07bb969cbb

commit_message:
Fix arg order of assertEqual and use assertTrue

assertEqual expects that the arguments provided to it should be
(expected, observed).If a particluar order is kept as a convention,
then it helps to provide a cleaner message to the developer if Unit Tests
fail. There are several Unit Test files where the arguments for assertEqual
have been swapped. This commit fixes the issue in python-neutronclient.

Additionally instead of using assertEqual(True,xxx), assertTrue(xxx) should
be used. The same has been fixed in this patch.

Partial-Bug: #1259292
Related-Bug: #1259292

Change-Id: I83ec45af75f61f8005a60efc8176db0df5cfbe9a

commit_message:
Fix coverage configuration and execution

A number of configuration errors prevent the successful creation of code
coverage. This corrects the .coveragerc source/omit setup and the tox
package name generation.

Change-Id: I5329955ee1e5101fe62012c6cae91e39f0fc96e4

commit_message:
Fix coverage configuration and execution

A number of configuration errors prevent the successful creation of code
coverage. This corrects the .coveragerc source/omit setup and the tox
package name generation.

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-October/076193.html

Change-Id: I2ee48d5b987cc26fe2de6d538ab278821100b278

Hi,Ivan Kolodyazhny	

I have found the change adding the attribute 'NAME_ATTR' for class VolumeBackup.[1]

The change[1] means that if a resource's attribute use display_name, not name, you should

add attribute 'NAME_ATTR' for the resource class. This change[1] removes redundant call 

find in resource manager, instead of it checks NAME_ATTR value. I know that Snapshot support filters

on server side using name and display_name. V2 Snapshot has parameter 'name', so I

delete attribute 'NAME_ATTR'.


[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/180533/"}, {'account_id': 17151, 'date': '2015-09-17 08:41:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Fix three resources not being deleted by using name

There are three resources: VolumeBackup, Snapshot, VolumeTransfer.
None of them can be deleted by using their names on V2.

For example, Snapshot client side filtering fails in the function
findall. The reason is that snapshot object
<class 'cinderclient.v2.volume_snapshots.Snapshot'> does not have
a attribute 'display_name'.

The response of /v2/{tenant_id}/backups/detail does not have
a parameter 'display_name', but have a parameter 'name'.
So class Snapshot does not need to define NAME_ATTR = 'display_name'.
The superclass of Snapshot 'Resource' has defined NAME_ATTR = 'name'.

Closes-Bug: #1497873
Closes-Bug: #1495428
Change-Id: I3c89fd9a82918e8a02385cfccb32dc9c3f4c4095

commit_message:
Fix heat polling error

Currently, while polling heat driver, return value of stacks and
deployments from heat driver are Objects of Stack and
SoftwareDeployment respectively. But the translator selector type
used is DICT instead of DOT, hence causing error.
This commit addresses the same.

Change-Id: I28648d9e73ead10467e5969dfb5e2a23e7278d12
Closes-Bug:#1503447

commit_message:
Fix coverage configuration and execution

A number of configuration errors prevent the successful creation of code
coverage. This corrects the .coveragerc source/omit setup and the tox
package name generation.

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-October/076193.html

Change-Id: Ie23fa6233a49e9db318b08d5a93e4dd7b0dae82d

commit_message:
Improve error messaging for accessing review.o.o

If the default OS user id does not match your gerrit username you
receive a blanket permission denied error message if retrieving the
list of gerrit projects fails.

This attempts to better identify the username, and provide a more
meaningful error message if the list projects function fails.

Change-Id: Ib05d3e7e4d772f42ad94d362bf34b4a36fc5cceb

commit_message:
Allow '+' in processor compatibility modes

PowerVM supports compatibility between processor levels. This
change allows the '+' character to be used in the flavor extra
spec values in place of '_Plus'.  For example: POWER6+ or
POWER6+_Enhanced rather than POWER6_Plus and POWER6_Plus_Enhanced.

Change-Id: I4e8ef3f82d66b582dec3ab8d8f2e199f51f021df
Closes-Bug: #1503908

commit_message:
Various fixes to get drivers functional (WIP)

This builds ontop of the last patch to get things functional. Includes:

    - Fix notifications layer to prepare events in their new format. Moves
      notificatin processing to the drivers themselves.

    - Repairs what used to be the TenantRouterCache and creates a new driver method
      for resolving resources by tenant. This fixes issues with current patch where
      events with no associated resource cause problems.

    - Converts Resource class to a namedtuple for now..

    - Avoids using a wrapper to update cache on the router driver--adds unnecessary
      complexity ATM

    - fixes some other method calls

    - Adds a driver method for listing ports of a logical resource

    - Adds get_state() driver method for reporting the state of the driver's
      resource. This is needed by the instance manager now that we've decoupled
       the instance state from logical resource state.

    - Finishes/fixes the router state sync'ing, adds required router driver
      method

    - Moves all usage of the akanda api client from instance manager to the router
      driver. ATM this client lib is router-specific.

    - Moves update_config, get_interfaces and is_alive to driver methods--
      different appliances will need to do these things in different ways
      (we currently use the akanda_client/router API service for them)

    - Moves router configuration to its own [router] group and deprecates
      the old options in [default]

This'll merge down to the patch below it when its ready.

Change-Id: Ib24f7e2415b7bce96cfe41d93fd1fcb88f6ecee8

commit_message:
Drop state machines work queue on rebalance if necessary

If a rug rebalances the ring and finds some of its local state
machines should no longer be managed, it should flush any queued
up work.

Change-Id: I7825d900cc54376d7a0e9680ca927b4c3e47119d

commit_message:
image set should not show the resource

the rest of OSC set commands do not show the resource after it has
been updated. unless the update fails then we report back a failure,
otherwise the user should assume everything went fine.

Change-Id: I2bd4188450c3853b4a1bc25f80fc9450cda32bdd

Looking more broadly at this patch, I don't think it's moving in the right direction.

If we had a working humanizeNumbers function I'd expect it to be broadly used, the same way Django's humanize filter is. It shouldn't be specifically associated with the quotas panel. If this weren't in a directory called "tech-debt" which is completely inappropriate I'd have given the patch a -2. However, the code shouldn't stay like it is.

We should either yank the broken humanizeNumbers function entirely, or place it appropriately for reuse.

On further review, it seems a viable solution for humaizeNubmers is underway ... https://review.openstack.org/#/c/199997'}, {'account_id': 17013, 'date': '2015-08-06 19:19:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Patch Set 6 was rebased'}, {'account_id': 17013, 'date': '2015-08-06 19:20:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

What if some other module outside quotas wants to use it in the future?"}, {'account_id': 17013, 'date': '2015-08-06 20:19:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

@Justin

I didn't originally write this function. I helped clean the aslant violations. 

Relevant patch is here https://review.openstack.org/#/c/199345 .

As part of code review in that patch, it was commented that the functions humanizeNumbers and truncate are used only in horizon.quota.js and so I created this to move them there.

I hope it makes sense. 

So if you feel that the function is more generic and usable elsewhere, sure it should not be moved.
Even then tech-debt is not the place for such reusable functions.
Let me know where it would make sense to have this function and I can move it there."}, {'account_id': 17013, 'date': '2015-08-06 20:20:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

commit_message:
Move humanize and truncate to horizon.quota.js

The functions humanize and truncate from horizon.utils
module are only used in horizon.quota.
This moves them over there and removes them the module.

This was inspired off comments in
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/199345

Co-Authored-By: Kyle Olivo<keolivo@thoughtworks.com>
Co-Authored-By: Richard Jones <r1chardj0n3s@gmail.com>
Change-Id: I48cf59cde7a673a19aa532b6515cdebf6f9d3638
Closes-Bug: #1480106

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-09-08 14:10:56.000000000', 'message': 'bootstrap: force dhclient to restart configuration on failures

dhclient shipped with CentOS bails out (after sending DHCPDECLINE) if
a duplicate address has been detected and `-1' ("one shot") flag has
been given. This kind of violates the RFC 2131 which prescribes
the client to restart the configuration process. On the other hand
retrying the configuration denies the `-1' switch purpose. CentOS'
developers choose to violate the RFC to obey the "one shot" behavior.
As a result network-scripts are unable to handle IP addresses conflict
and fail to bring the interfaces up during the OS boot sequence.

Suppose there are some bootstrap nodes booted by a different master
node (say, by a previously deployed one) in the admin/pxe network.
The DHCP server on the current (the newly deployed) master node is
not aware of those nodes, thus the IP addresses leased to the nodes
collide with the ones of the (stale) nodes booted by a different
master node. As a result some nodes will fail to boot.

In order to solve the problem specify the PERSISTENT_DHCLIENT flag
in the ifcfg-${boot_iface} config file, so dhclient will retry
the configuration.

Closes-Bug: #1492307
Change-Id: Ica89fc05d4f936feb3066d27a8fb9a24bc36b55c
'}]
commit_message:
bootstrap: force dhclient to restart configuration on failures

dhclient shipped with CentOS bails out (after sending DHCPDECLINE) if
a duplicate address has been detected and `-1' ("one shot") flag has
been given. This kind of violates the RFC 2131 which prescribes
the client to restart the configuration process. On the other hand
retrying the configuration denies the `-1' switch purpose. CentOS'
developers choose to violate the RFC to obey the "one shot" behavior.
As a result network-scripts are unable to handle IP addresses conflict
and fail to bring the interfaces up during the OS boot sequence.

Suppose there are some bootstrap nodes booted by a different master
node (say, by a previously deployed one) in the admin/pxe network.
The DHCP server on the current (the newly deployed) master node is
not aware of those nodes, thus the IP addresses leased to the nodes
collide with the ones of the (stale) nodes booted by a different
master node. As a result some nodes will fail to boot.

In order to solve the problem specify the PERSISTENT_DHCLIENT flag
in the ifcfg-${boot_iface} config file, so dhclient will retry
the configuration.

Closes-Bug: #1492307

commit_message:
Fix project name encoded in project controller

As the project name is passed to the project controller as a part of URL
and URL can be encoded, this commit change the controller to decode the
project name parameter with decodeURIComponent() before anything. It is
necessary both to exibit the name properly and pass it to the server
side api.

Change-Id: I03472c54259daf5c6bcd85dbdd3b59545e391cae

commit_message:
Switch from single key to key-per wwpn pairing

In npiv.py, a string mapping of the wwpn pairs are being saved to
system_metadata. In some cases, the string value generated can be
quite large. To prevent this from happening, this change is to move
from a single key to one key per wwpn pairing. We differentiate the
keys by appending a unique number to the end of the key in
_set_fabric_meta. This change requires that _get_fabric_meta also be
modified to accomodate the changes in how the mappings are now stored.

Change-Id: I72e65957edec41405aad30768dab547134b5edce
Closes-Bug: #1492291

commit_message:
Fixed murano error on show actions

Added call to ExecutionDriver.__init__() to initialize variable.
Added ExecutionDriver.self.inspect_builtin_methods(...) to add
executable methods.

Change-Id: Ia51ffb4062b5b3e0e3948589987f6e48cf94468c
DocImpact:
Closes-Bug: #1503443

Fix non-ascii issue with object commands

Escape the container and object name whenever it is used
as URL.

Closes-Bug: #1503508

2) introduce new method named is_block_device into utils/hardware.py which will check whether device is actually block/char.

3) call this check inside of manager, https://github.com/stackforge/fuel-agent/blob/master/fuel_agent/manager.py#L324-L325

4) cover new changes with unit tests.

(2 comments)

Looks good thought but I still have a concern for the rolling out plan. Please see my inline.'}, {'account_id': 9625, 'date': '2015-09-28 18:38:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

I talked to Alan on the IRC channel about this spec, so I'll just re-state here what we talked about. 

There are two problems this spec is dealing with. First is that container listings can get stale (e.g. returning listings of objects that have been expired and should no longer be in the list). The second problem is the scalability of the current expirer. 

My issue is the proposed solution for the second problem. By moving the expiring functionality to the auditor, you would break the nice "feature" that the expirer works for any DiskFile implementation. The current expirer doesn't need to know what the stored file layout looks like. By moving that functionality to the auditor, other DiskFile implementation would automatically lose object expiration until they implement their own expiring daemon to scan and expire files/objects in their storage systems.'}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2015-09-28 20:24:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1

That is a nice feature of the current design, and may be argument to consider when we're planning an eviction the existing implementation after a suitable migration period.  We should try to make sure this spec doesn't make to strong a specific claim about that plan - we need to wait and see.

In the short term we'll have to accept having both anyway.  So you're really looking ahead to a point where we have a an alternative solution that works "better" (by some definition) and then questioning the time frame for an eviction plan and I suggest we punt.

At that time it may make more sense to expand the new implementation to make it easier for out-of-tree plugins to leverage it's capabilities/scalability - or it may make sense to maintain what we already have for some time longer than a few releases (indefinitely?) - but those are down the road problems...

And either way that shouldn't prevent development/improvement/iteration on the reference implementation.  

Still worth keeping in mind, tho.  It might be possible that a solution exists which would have the properties Alan is after while still being mostly outside of the object/container servers/implementation - but I'm curious what the container backend changes end up looking like exactly.

Without indexes on created at, or some kind of name mangling, I think it'll be rather difficult to find a solution that isn't constantly paging all the containers.  I think targeting specifically the problem of pushing through a number of container delete rows quickly (using bulk usync_db replicate requests) could speed up the consistency on the container listings quite a bit without deviating from the existing design greatly - although that's not really a specific design requirement i have or anything - just an idea that might reduce the cost/risk of implementing a solution for the immediate pain more cheaply.  If getting the rows in sync with expiration more quickly *also* needs to be supplemented with some sort of filters in the listing by stuffing something in content-type or w/e remains an open question to me.  I think the main pain-point is having the bytes in the container more quickly reflect the expired objects - and it seems like the quickest way to trigger the insertion of a named delete row is to keep a tight index on what needs to happen when.'}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2015-09-28 20:37:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+2

(6 comments)

seems reasonable to iterate on I think'}, {'account_id': 995, 'date': '2015-10-08 18:54:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-08 18:55:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: -Verified

commit_message:
Team Structure policy document

Added a new Fuel Policy Documents section with a new policy document on
Fuel Team Structure. Following additional changes were made to make this
patch build cleanly:

 * basepython = python to prevent tox on Debian from using python3
 * autogenerated doc/source/index.rst added to .gitignore
 * policy directory and symlink created and reflected in header template

Change-Id: I66149c3edcb99b8b6f130518fe6ca8239864036a

commit_message:
Refactored documents as per neutron standards.

This patch does below changes to comply with existing neutron's devref
documents.

Below changes are done as part of this patch:
 - Added standard headers.
 - Added new devref document about command extensions.
 - Re-arranged the content of index.rst to make it modular.
 - Rename filename and heading to avoid confusions.
 - Fix tox issues.

Co-Authored-By: Cathy Zhang <cathy.h.zhang@huawei.com>

commit_message:
Add useful watcher '__repr__' function

When a workers watchers are iterated over and
say printed to stderr/stdout the default '__repr__'
doesn't provide much value; so instead of the default
provide our own that adds slightly more value.

Change-Id: I8f82a732ad3d9f0ce0ec5857d5d883b3b5f2ff1d

commit_message:
Add ipaddress>=1.0.14 to global-requirements.txt

Required by python-tripleoclient

Recent activity: https://github.com/phihag/ipaddress/commits/master
Latest release: July 16, 2015
Code is well-written and has good unit test coverage
Python 3 compatible: This functionality is included in Py3
License is Python Software Foundation License
Packages appear to exist for RH and Ubuntu
https://admin.fedoraproject.org/pkgdb/package/python-ipaddress/
http://packages.ubuntu.com/wily/python-ipaddress
There does not appear to be an existing requirement covering this
functionality

Change-Id: I02b798d4f9cbc649bd18bd087cbfeb08ac3fc9ba

commit_message:
In py3, use csv instead of unicodecsv module

Py3 support in unicodecsv is less than perfect.
Currently, even simple writerow to stdout is failing.
Py3's 'csv' module is much more stable. More importantly,
it supports Unicode natively, which was the reason to
introduce 'unicodecsv' in the first place.

After this change, unicodecsv will be used only in Py2.

TODO: unicodecsv is still requirement for this package
  even if not used in Py3. Conditional requirements file
  cloud fix that.

Change-Id: I16a5aea7356acd6d0065bbdfc4109ef4a06333bb

commit_message:
Realizing SFC (1b/5): Adding additional tox and test settings.

This patch is the continuation of
"https://review.openstack.org/#/c/227069/" patch and addresses
additional tox and test settings required by a developer for
validating his/her changes before submitting code for review.

Below changes are done as part of this patch-set:
 - Added listed toolkits for sanity checks.
    tools/check_i18n.py
    tools/check_i18n_test_case.txt
    tools/check_unit_test_structure.sh
    tools/clean.sh
    tools/i18n_cfg.py
    tools/install_venv.py
    tools/install_venv_common.py
    tools/tox_install.sh
    tools/with_venv.sh
 - Added .coveragerc and .pylintrc
 - Cherry picked changes from https://review.openstack.org/#/c/227820/

Change-Id: I0b774c3ed1a1ff7cf4d26d6da786e95dc54f8c8e

commit_message:
Add oslo.versionedobjects src job to nova experimental

These two projects are highly interrelated and being able to sniff
test before releases would be helpful to reduce churn.

Change-Id: I8bdceab146c451fb45ab109d7595d946e3cc0d96

commit_message:
py3: Replace unicode with six.text_type

The unicode type was renamed to str in Python 3. Use six.text_type to
make the modified code compatible with Python 2 and Python 3.

The initial patch was generated by the unicode operation of the sixer
tool on: bin/* swift/ test/.

Change-Id: I9e13748ccde36ee8110756202d55d3ae945d4860

commit_message:
vmware: set default value in fake _db_content when creating objects

There is a potential KeyError when creating objects and populating the
_db_content dictionary in the fake module.  We should use setdefault to
make sure _db_content is ready to set an object value the first time
it's used.

Closes-Bug: #1501080

Change-Id: Ia3aaeb9e1ba95f33eb6004cab2df133a12a4361d

commit_message:
make curl fail on pypi errors

This will make curl fail on pypi errors, and should prevent corrupt
images from pypi going offline for a few hours randomly, which it does
from time to time.

Closes-Bug: #1503909

Change-Id: Ib4a740b7d1772e1e36aa701e42d3ac0f0ee12883

In the next step of running VPN functional tests for neutron
commits, we need to test the jobs non-voting. We currently have
the VPN functional jobs in the experimental queue. However, we
can't move them to the check queue, as those jobs are voting for
the neutron-vpnaas project.

We also have new functional jobs, which do the same thing, but
use different job names, have different "target" names passed to
the hook scripts and tox.ini, and which use a single, parameterized
job template.

To resolve this situation, the plan is to use the new jobs for
neutron, as non-voting.

Current jobs --> target names
gate-neutron-vpnaas-dsvm-functional --> dsvm-functional
gate-neutron-vpnaas-dsvm-functional-sswan --> dsvm-functional-sswan

New jobs --> target names
gate-neutron-vpnaas-test-dsvm-functional --> functional
gate-neutron-vpnaas-test-dsvm-functional-sswan --> functional-sswan

To support this, this commit does several things:

- Modify tox.ini to use the new targets "functional" and "functional-sswan".
- Renames coverage targets accordingly in tox.ini.
- Renames conflicting "functional" helper target to "func-deps".
- Adjust hook scripts to use new target names.
- Add temp clause to rename existing target names to the new names.

With this commit, we can test that the current voting jobs for
neutron-vpnaas, run under the new target naming, and can test that
the new experimental jobs run as well. Neutron commits can test
the new jobs via commit Ieea93753e352ccb09f65aac12c8c81c1d96593ac.

Once verified, we can make the new jobs voting and remove the
(redundant) old jobs.

Change-Id: I9de55d136e24b201d81568d68d2756878677a765

commit_message:
VPNaaS: Support for new functional jobs

In the next step of running VPN functional tests for neutron
commits, we need to test the jobs non-voting. We currently have
the VPN functional jobs in the experimental queue. However, we
can't move them to the check queue, as those jobs are voting for
the neutron-vpnaas project.

We also have new functional jobs, which do the same thing, but
use different job names, have different "target" names passed to
the hook scripts and tox.ini, and which use a single, parameterized
job template.

To resolve this situation, the plan is to use the new jobs for
neutron, as non-voting.

Current jobs --> target names
gate-neutron-vpnaas-dsvm-functional --> dsvm-functional
gate-neutron-vpnaas-dsvm-functional-sswan --> dsvm-functional-sswan

New jobs --> target names
gate-neutron-vpnaas-test-dsvm-functional --> functional
gate-neutron-vpnaas-test-dsvm-functional-sswan --> functional-sswan

To support this, this commit does several things:

- Modify tox.ini to use the new targets "functional" and "functional-sswan".
- Renames coverage targets accordingly in tox.ini.
- Renames conflicting "functional" helper target to "func-deps".
- Adjust hook scripts to use new target names.
- Add temp clause to rename existing target names to the new names.

With this commit, we can test that the current voting jobs for
neutron-vpnaas, run under the new target naming, and can test that
the new experimental jobs run as well. Neutron commits can test
the new jobs via commit Ieea93753e352ccb09f65aac12c8c81c1d96593ac.

Once verified, we can make the new jobs voting and remove the
(redundant) old jobs.

Change-Id: I9de55d136e24b201d81568d68d2756878677a765

commit_message:
Fix obj_to_primitive() when used with a manifest

Previously, we required any child object version bump to come with a
bump to any objects that included it as a parent. That allowed us to use
the version of the object at the top of a tree to determine whether we
should do a backport as part of a to_primitive operation. With manifests,
that's no longer the case. So, if we have been requested a version other
than the current one, OR if we have a manifest, we need to run the make-
compatible step. We will end up doing this all the tiem now, but it should
be very quick if nothing needs backporting.

commit_message:
diskimage-builder element cleanups for dib-lint

Since I6c5a962260741dcf6f89da9a33b96372a719b7b0 dib has had a
standardised method for ensuring consistency of tracing and error
detection.  Bring the tracing for these elements up to that standard,
but maintain the status-quo of flags such as "-e" and "pipefail" by
adding ignore flags where appropriate (we can update these separately
to avoid breakage)

Other minor changes are alphabetical-ordering in the element-deps
files and permissions on prepare-node script

With this, "tox -edib" passes

Change-Id: Ibba1dadb9e819f94294c9d583b83ff698252f93f

commit_message:
Fix broken unit tests

With release of six module version 1.10.0 several our unit tests
started to fail because of usage of not strict constructions.

Changes:
1) Manila unit test
"manila.tests.share.test_api.ShareAPITestCase.test_extend_quota_error"
used str for int substitution. So, use int data for int substitution.

2) Module 'manila.share.drivers.hp.hp_3par_mediator' was using
LOG.exception function when no traceback were exist it led to
AttributeError on py34. So, replace all usages of 'LOG.exception'
with 'LOG.error' where no raised exceptions exist.

Change-Id: Ic5b37bfb9d939d03f6ff68bc53d134bf9e5f996e
Closes-Bug: #1503969

commit_message:
Part 3: Adding ACL functional tests.

Added functional tests for CLI commands.
Added functional tests for client API.

Modified ACL client API functional test not to use behavior class
as per recent change in secrets, containers, and orders.

Change-Id: Ibacf33e834daa2c70ef1b0032495bbe443957cac

commit_message:
Update kilo for new dev work - 8 Oct 2015

Updates all repo SHAs to open up work on 11.2.4

A temporary cap for requests is implemented until the following bug
is fixed upstream:
https://bugs.launchpad.net/python-glanceclient/+bug/1476770

Change-Id: I42df90310c5fecb1657afd272e49b646ceaa129f

commit_message:
Create training-labs repository

Training labs is the labs folder under training-guides. Since the
Icehouse release, labs section is moving faster than the rest of the
training guides and does not really sync with the documentation content
in there. Thus, giving the scripts a new home will make it easier
to develop, test and release the scripts.

This patch is to address the change of name from openstack-labs.
  * Deletes openstacklabs spec.

Change-Id: Ibddf1191acb7d9cf81f1321699cc9b0039ddbb1e

[{'created': '2015-10-08 14:13:00.000000000', 'message': "Validate cluster in node group creation

Currently if user pass incorrect or invalid cluster ID to nodegroup
creation POST request the 500 Internal Server error is occur. That's
not the way we should handle invalid input data. Let's throw
404 Not Found if invalid cluster ID is passed.

Closes-Bug: #1494320

Change-Id: Ief3754367690c83021f1e636f58311f0c02c941a
Signed-off-by: Igor Kalnitsky <igor@kalnitsky.org>
"}]
commit_message:
Validate cluster in node group creation

Currently if user pass incorrect or invalid cluster ID to nodegroup
creation POST request the 500 Internal Server error is occur. That's
not the way we should handle invalid input data. Let's throw
404 Not Found if invalid cluster ID is passed.

Closes-Bug: #1494320

Change-Id: Ief3754367690c83021f1e636f58311f0c02c941a
Signed-off-by: Igor Kalnitsky <igor@kalnitsky.org>

commit_message:
Port test_quobyte to Python 3

Modify assertRaisesAndMessageMatches() to tolerate subclasses. On
Python 3, a permission error now raises an exception PermissionError
which is a subclass of OSError, whereas the test expected exactly the
OSError type.

Partial-Implements: blueprint cinder-python3
Change-Id: Ia232c27de6a67eafad30b25301531e292fe349dc

commit_message:
Assign VIPs not only for controllers' node group

Recently we had an assumption that VIPs could be allocated only for
controllers, so we used controllers' node group to do allocation.
That was incorrect assumption, and led to incorrect behaviour for
envs with standalone-* roles (e.g. standalone-keystone) if it's
in separate node group.

So let's use proper node group for VIP allocation based on provided
node role(s) information. Obviously, all nodes with provided node
role(s) MUST have the same node group, otherwise the error will be
thrown.

Closes-Bug: #1487021
Change-Id: I0ae2e5395fb4fe5cd921bc336718cc94003f156d

commit_message:
carbonara: optimize resampling

This changes the resampling method we used to have by not doing any real
resampling like Pandas used too. The `resampling' method from Pandas insert a
lot of empty points filled with NaN as value if your timeserie is sparse –
which is a typical case in Carbonara/Gnocchi. This ends up creating timeseries
with millions of empty points, consuming hundreds of MB of memory for nothing.

This method inspired by Jeff on https://github.com/pydata/pandas/issues/11217
implements a simpler versino of what `resample` does: it groups the sample by
timestamp, and then compute an aggregation method on them. This avoids creating
thousands of useless points and ends up being much faster and consume a *LOT*
less memory.

Benchmarked: for a new timeserie with 10k measures with 10-80k points by
archive this reduces the memory usage of metricd from 2 GB to 100 MB and the
compute speed of the most complicated aggregations like percentile to 15min to
20s (45× speed improvement).

Change-Id: I1b8718508bdd4633e7324949b76184efc3718ede

commit_message:
match archive policy rule based on longest match

currently, we use the first archive policy rule that we match based
on querying the existing rules. this list of rules is unordered.
this patch explicitly orders rules by metric_pattern so match against
the longest match first.

Change-Id: I4cc99ccbf98c1920d46ae259c81275953e9bfb03
Co-Authored-By: Alejandro Comisario <alejandro@nubeliu.com>
Closes-bug: #1501344

commit_message:
carbonara: drop empty points from resample before combine

This should make things a little faster on big series.

Change-Id: Ice5e7825a53695c80fd8a831f1147686024ab0c5

commit_message:
carbonara: only resample on the last point

If the BoundTimeSerie contains a lot of point, this is way faster to use
the last point only, and it's enough since that's the only point we care
about.

Change-Id: Ia3d8c2291824b8dfb2e5d587faa195c9d7ca3dc6

locks are optimistic, and if the same data gets modifyed concurrently

commit_message:
Retry-on-deadlock added to modify package db api

On some HA database deployments such as MySQL Galera the transaction
locks are optimistic, and if the same data gets modifyed concurrently
DB server may throw a DBDeadlock error which is intended to be handled
by the caller app.

This patch adds appropriate retrying logic into the catalog db api
methods, so the operation to upload, modify or delete the package gets
retryed if the deadlock occurs due to this optimistic locking behavior.
It uses oslo_db_api.wrap_db_retry helper decorator from oslo library.

Closes-Bug: #1502589
Change-Id: I8d7b3dfb02a31eba6d55ba0bf89ac0cf05f1313d

commit_message:
Removing fixed settings inside the glance-cache.conf

Using same overrides for the admin_user and admin_tenant_name
as the main glance API configuration.
This fix will make sure that the glance services will use the
same set of admin settings across multiple configuration files.

Change-Id: I8009cd1b9f5548f5272d37b48ca7b43e7a0b2f86

[{'created': '2015-10-02 20:55:59.000000000', 'message': "Fix swarm bay failure reporting

The old method of detecting failures was very likely to fail in
many cases because it relied on all bay services being started by
the time cloud-init finished. This is a problem because the bay
services are started asynchronously and can take quite a while to
start.

The new method relies on systemd's OnFailure directive to kick off
specific service units when a failure is detected. Both the swarm
agent and manager have their own failure service so that we are
not overloading a single wait condition with multiple potential
failures.

commit_message:
Fix swarm bay failure reporting

The old method of detecting failures was very likely to fail in
many cases because it relied on all bay services being started by
the time cloud-init finished. This is a problem because the bay
services are started asynchronously and can take quite a while to
start.

The new method relies on systemd's OnFailure directive to kick off
specific service units when a failure is detected. Both the swarm
agent and manager have their own failure service so that we are
not overloading a single wait condition with multiple potential
failures.

Change-Id: I7ce4be567517fe948dde0ac7225996967196c9e8
Closes-bug: #1502329

Fixes Python 3 str issue in ConfigDrive creation

ConfigDrive creation fails when writing metadata to file
due to a str to bytes conversion issue.

commit_message:
Amended install instructions in README.rst

Purpose: helps users avoid several installation errors
Changes:
- added instruction to install requirements using pip
- added instruction to install required packages build-essential,
libssl-dev, libffi-dev

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1503094
Closes-Bug: #1503095

Change-Id: I484eda2e16edb2039add38c92720eb15d9274fd1

commit_message:
Added MAINTAINERS to top-level repo directory

In a consensus reached in a proposal for code review process
change [1], and proposed team structure policy document [2],
adding MAINTAINERS files in repositories.

Please note, that this file is written in YAML format in order
to allow further automation around code review process.

[1] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-August/072406.html
[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/225376/1

Change-Id: Ia529e842a428d64f28b32c4c4e4ad168ee24820b

commit_message:
Backported bugfix 1415986 to stable/juno:

  * Added dependency on oslo.serialization>=1.0.0<=1.2.0
    (pulled in by other openstack services in stable/juno,
    such as Keystone).
  * Changed import of oslo_serialization.jsonutils to
    oslo.serialization 1.0.0 (oslo_serialization is a
    1.2.0ism).

Change-Id: I244b85e3af642e5c9c5a7e515c449716dece1597

commit_message:
Update path to subunit2html in post_test_hook

Per:

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-August/072982.html

The location of subunit2html changed on the images in the gate
so update the path used in the post_test_hook.

Long-term we should just use what's in devstack-gate.

Closes-Bug: #1491646
(cherry picked from commit d75f79f67c176a38d41fcc5f8794d5956ac65ace)

This also adds a gate_hook to invoke d-g for env prepping. It merely
triggers main devstack-gate script. We need the hook because our new
neutronclient jobs define gate_hook function that points to it, and in
that case devstack-gate does NOT trigger its main script, leaving it up
to the hook.

Depends-on: I8549db52fa5b752202ac7f019b3e1931a697e337
Change-Id: If37743547f739e494501bbc5dc3bb214293919fa

Adrian"}, {'account_id': 10263, 'date': '2015-09-25 23:35:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

@Surojit, I tried contacting you on IRC and also left a comment here. This patch is kind of urgent for TLS to get completed by Liberty release, so I took it. 
Also I left a comment for my -1.

Hope this makes thing clear.'}, {'account_id': 15311, 'date': '2015-09-27 16:41:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

@Madhuri,
I am sorry to say that I do not find this as a sound justification.

1. TLS is important for Liberty release. As there was no activity on this patch since 17th Sept, Adrian asked me to take this up on 23rd[1]. I started working on this patch on 24th, clearly declaring on it, as a comment.
2. You left -1, on my patchse, without providing any feedback/review comment. But you continued with most of the content of the patch.
3. You looked for me in IRC, I am sorry you could not find me. You left a comment on the review and you did not give a turn around time, not even 12 hours, whereas we are in different time-zones, I suppose.

I am curious to find out what prompted you to take over the patch-set#5, without providing review comments. 



[1] - http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/irclogs/%23openstack-containers/%23openstack-containers.2015-09-23.log.html#t2015-09-23T17:33:14'}, {'account_id': 10206, 'date': '2015-09-27 17:56:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: -Workflow

@Surojit,

I don't think there is so much to discuss about it. It's simple, just take this patch and continue.
What actually matters to me is the project, not my or your work.
I am sorry, you get it wrong.

Also please read my comment on Patch Set 5 at Sep 26 4:18 PM."}, {'account_id': 15311, 'date': '2015-09-28 07:33:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

@Madhuri,
Appreciate your spirit and trust me we are on the same side to achieve the betterment of the project!
I am sorry to misunderstand your action :(

For the healthiness of the community, I would suggest that it would be better to take forward someone else's work by merging the code first or creating dependent patch-set or providing constructive review comments. That would definitely save us this kind of misunderstanding going forward. Just imagine the community, where people will resubmit a patch, instead of providing review comments - I can't even visualize it.
As of now, if you allow me, I would like to continue to work on the same and look forward to seeing your valuable review comments.
Towards Liberty ..."}, {'account_id': 10263, 'date': '2015-09-28 07:53:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Make Kubernetes API call secure

This patch makes API call to Kubernetes secure using the certificate
and key.

Co-Authored-By: Madhuri Kumari<madhuri.kumari@intel.com>
Co-Authored-By: OTSUKA, Yuanying<yuanying@fraction.jp>
Depends-On: I76b0f91f0c44f9880980e35c6b8856ea48ed3ce1
Change-Id: Id4dceb83f67b80f5b39e3047011f9e34e840359d
Partially-Implements: blueprint secure-kubernetes

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-02 14:01:06.000000000', 'message': "Avoid transcending with find

Find doesn't like listings disappearing while its trying to find them,
in this case if a PID directory disappears while find is running,
it can't find out if it was a file or directory so seems to assume
it was a file and prints the path in the listing (-prune effects
directories only). cpio then fails because the path doesn't exist.

We have to resort to storing the file list in a temp file and then append
