commit_message:
Avoid transcending /proc with find

Find doesn't like listings disappearing while its trying to find them,
in this case if a PID directory disappears while find is running. Using
-xdev prevents find from going into ./proc and as a side effect /dev
will also be avoided which is mounted on boot so not needed either.

Change-Id: Iaa282e58d81d533ad4445da0a44200dd14bf0850
Closes-bug: #1502142

commit_message:
Enable hardcoded_bind_all_interfaces Bandit test

The hardcoded_bind_all_interfaces checks that we're not binding to
all interfaces. Keystone needs to do this for backwards
compatibility so the current uses are marked as `nosec`.

Change-Id: I8243f679e0dcff81c9482e0381526e997725d7fd

Instance hostname is generated by displayname, currently, displayname
can be '----', and other Non-ASCII character such as Chinese characters,
sanitize_hostname will return empty in such cases.

This patch adds a helper function _default_host_name to give an instance
default name if sanitize_hostname returns empty hostname. And,
sanitize_hostname will truncated to 63 if the host name is too long.

Also Window, Linux, and Dnsmasq have different limitation:

Windows: 255 (net_bios limit to 15, but window will truncate it)

commit_message:
Give instance default hostname if hostname is empty

Instance hostname is generated by displayname, currently, displayname
can be '----', and other Non-ASCII character such as Chinese characters,
sanitize_hostname will return empty in such cases.

This patch adds a helper function _default_host_name to give an instance
default name if sanitize_hostname returns empty hostname. And,
sanitize_hostname will truncated to 63 if the host name is too long.

Also Window, Linux, and Dnsmasq have different limitation:

Windows: 255 (net_bios limit to 15, but window will truncate it)
Linux: 64
Dnsmasq: 63

Due to nova-network will leverage dnsmasq to set hostname, so we chose
63.

Besides, added more test cases to cover sanitize_hostname.

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1495388
Co-authored-by: Alex Xu <hejie.xu@intel.com>

(cherry picked from commit bc6f30de953303604625e84ad2345cfb595170d2)

Conflicts:
	nova/tests/unit/compute/test_compute_api.py
	nova/tests/unit/test_utils.py
	nova/utils.py

Change-Id: I443b51e0576cf657d96e498d6700bfc34d987301

commit_message:
Demo: Use Actions directive for actions on Images

This allows the use of the directive to show actions
for images panel.

This patch will be merged into relevant parent patches
once the directive work stabilizes.

Co-Authored-By: Errol Pais<epais@thoughtworks.com>

Change-Id: I89b84dae90a765cad286d7c99789a311c7a6501a
Partially-Implements: blueprint angularize-images-table

commit_message:
Fix InstanceV1 backports to use context

This fixes the InstanceV1 and InstanceListV1 backport code to properly
initialize the temporary objects with a context. Without them, the
objects are orphaned and can't do certain things.

This should be backported to liberty

Closes-Bug: #1503708
Change-Id: I537734c0f10110ac64799cc1232edbc18a16c794
(cherry picked from commit e571d88604353a0443ae4ca24e3ce72fb4c615f2)

commit_message:
Ignore bashate long-line warnings (E006)

Since Ic2532676e46e93f129d590d1fa7a044ef65f50fb bashate warns on
long-lines.  Traditionally, for whatever reason, devstack hasn't cared
too much about long lines unless it really damages readability.

So ignore this to avoid thousands of warnings on the long lines.  Note
even though released bashate doesn't have this, ignoring a missing
test doesn't matter.

Change-Id: I16aeaa3b334fac1eec5085f2cfe26c81c53023a8

commit_message:
Implement a fall back URL for get-pip.py

This patch implements a fall-back URL for get-pip.py to cater for situations
where https://bootstrap.pypa.io/get-pip.py is not available (like today).

The deployer may still override the URL for the bootstrap process.

The patch also implements the fallback process in the pip_install role to
ensure that the fall back also takes place when the playbooks are run.

Change-Id: I33de85feacb633c10ed828f5d005992da6ca8a1e

can we updated all of the SHAs using the tool sources-branch-updater.sh which will use the actual SHA and mark the date as to when it was done. In this way we'd be able to pickup changes that are actually being made in the "stable/liberty" branch which at this point should exists within all projects. This would also allow us to run ahead of the tag such that we're pulling in bug fixes faster. 

Usage:
  ./scripts/sources-branch-updater.sh -b stable/liberty --service-file <file-name>

At this stage I'm not against the use of the named tag however when we release our own stable liberty I would be against staying on the named tags as we've found that tags generally languish behind major security and bug fixes. Additionally with the new semantic versions it'lli be a pain to manage all of the various tags while our tooling will simply keep us at a locked point in time which is forever within the projects git history.'}, {'account_id': 6816, 'date': '2015-10-05 14:38:52.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 10.'}, {'account_id': 7353, 'date': '2015-10-05 14:41:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-05 16:27:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Verified+1

commit_message:
Update all SHA's to Liberty branch SHA's

The git SHA for django-openstack-auth is carried temporarily in order
to resolve https://bugs.launchpad.net/openstack-ansible/+bug/1497679

Closes-Bug: #1497679
Implements: blueprint liberty-release
Change-Id: I6c73b7774a56cb48d8e0e2399bd48322f303ea54

commit_message:
node-list support get-node-by-instance_id

ironic RESTful-api support below api:
'get /v1/nodes?instance_uuid={instance_uuid}'
'get /v1/nodes/detail?instance_uuid={instance_uuid}'

cli currently use node-show to support get-node-by-instance
(get /v1/nodes/detail?instance_uuid={instance_uuid}. it lack
RESTful api 'get /v1/nodes?instance_uuid={instance_uuid}'.

cli add subcommand on  node-list:
    ironic node-list --instance_id {uuid}
    ironic node-list --instance_id {uuid} --detail

Change-Id: I7b0f1d06ee8dcd8ec27689e1d4bed0269d59fbe1
Closes-Bug: #1416620

commit_message:
Support multiple addresses assignment with ifcfg

Currently only the first IPv4/v6 address is assigned to a NIC
even if multiple addresses are specified in config file.
With this change, ifcfg implementation can configure multiple
IPv4/v6 addresses for a NIC.
Also this enables os-net-config to configure IPv6 netmasks.

Change-Id: I31b39abae36e0620dbbcb1001fa51f5ca2bd9ea2

commit_message:
Enable translation of firstapp

Enable translation of firstapp. This change enables sending of strings
to our translation server. Once we have translations, we can start
building. Create empty firstapp.pot to trigger the process.

Change-Id: I55210bd8292300e8b42e62eb34c0ba80a89cb6d9
Depends-On: I57780453bd8ee214d10b646e7a989de7e33fa2a9

commit_message:
Set Octavia as the reference LBaaSv2 driver

Requires skipping some of the pool tests as they are taking too long.  We will
need to revisit those and find a way to re-enable them.
Sets up a minimal set of "happy path" tests for neutron gate

Depends-On: Ifce40b0af9da715d44bab8ec437f844ccf638f52
Depends-On: I0434b8ced144ab08413b91569bd008295ef1784e
Change-Id: I8e72a63f3ac9d3b605779b49112a1f9924845c5c
Implements: blueprint lbaas-ref-octavia

Rework fuleweb_test framworks for automation generating TestCase

put yaml conf into fuelweb_test/environments
define Case in fuelweb_test/acceptance_tests
proboscis generate group of test for each case and config

For sen new test plans use Jenkins script.
    for all matrix:
        sh -x "utils/jenkins/system_tests.sh" -L -j $JOB_NAME -t test -w "$WORKSPACE" -i $ISO_PATH -o --group=acceptance -o --show-plan -k -K

    for some case:
        sh -x "utils/jenkins/system_tests.sh" -L -j $JOB_NAME -t test -w "$WORKSPACE" -i $ISO_PATH -o --group=acceptance.create_deploy_delete -o --show-plan -k -K

    for some case and config
        sh -x "utils/jenkins/system_tests.sh" -L -j $JOB_NAME -t test -w "$WORKSPACE" -i $ISO_PATH -o --group=acceptance.create_deploy_delete.case1 -o --show-plan -k -K

commit_message:
Template based tests with yaml configs

Rework fuleweb_test framworks for automation generating TestCase

put yaml confs into fuelweb_test/system_tests_templates
define Case in fuelweb_test/actions_tests
proboscis generate group of test for each case and config

For sen new test plans use Jenkins script.
    for all matrix:
        sh -x "utils/jenkins/system_tests.sh" -L -j $JOB_NAME \
            -t test -w "$WORKSPACE" -i $ISO_PATH \
            -o --group=system_test \
            -o --show-plan -k -K

    for some case and all configuration:
        sh -x "utils/jenkins/system_tests.sh" -L -j $JOB_NAME \
            -t test -w "$WORKSPACE" -i $ISO_PATH \
            -o --group=system_test.create_deploy_ostf \
            -o --show-plan -k -K

    for some case and some config
        sh -x "utils/jenkins/system_tests.sh" -L -j $JOB_NAME \
            -t test -w "$WORKSPACE" -i $ISO_PATH \
            -o --group=system_test.create_deploy_ostf.1ctrl_1comp_1cinder_neutronVLAN \
            -o --show-plan -k -K

    for run all destroy controllers failover cases
        sh -x "utils/jenkins/system_tests.sh" -L -j $JOB_NAME \
            -t test -w "$WORKSPACE" -i $ISO_PATH \
            -o --group=system_test.failover.destroy_controllers.3ctrl_2comp_1cndr_neutronVLAN \
            -o --show-plan -k -K

Change-Id: I81eeb0df84a0f373be029f20ec6c53e8d3596596
Implements blueprint template-based-testcases

commit_message:
Move enabled directory to app_catalog

This commit moves the enabled directory from
the root of the repo to the app_catalog
directory. This will allow the directory to
be included in the python package, and
matches the layout of a few other Horizon-
related projects.

Change-Id: Icb63b8c996826fccc2ba785be0321396d8a803fd

commit_message:
Run db-sync as ironic-inspector user

We switched to root-wrap, so we need to run the db-sync as
the same user as the openstack-ironic-inspector server.

Change-Id: I3ca9767bc4925ae5f386fb311b71134e180cbd73

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC

commit_message:
Automated setup using Vagrant + Virtualbox

Automate the setup described in the devstack test instructions.

This will create a 2 nodes devstack (controller + compute),
where OVN is used as the Open vSwitch backend.

Change-Id: I6d6f77c8d19e4496c1c4f516d403410dd2799009

commit_message:
Handle memcache pool arguments collectively

Tracing the usage of memcache pool arguments goes through 3 different
functions and involves slightly tweaking the parameter names each time.

This was making it impossible to reason with so collapse down the
memcache arguments into a dictionary that is passed around.

Change-Id: I8bd5cb50183795d9b8fd953dabd935f15f03a385

commit_message:
Add commands to show image metadata

- cinder image-metadata-show volume_id
This command can be used to show the image metadata associated
with the specific volume.

Partially implements: bp support-modify-volume-image-metadata

Change-Id: I960af66038b47c1206619b99a2bb5ae561a59c4f

commit_message:
tox.ini: Fix cover by giving the source directory explicitly

By default, testr assumes that the name of distribution
([metadata]name in setup.cfg) matches the name of the source directory.
However, they are different for this project.  Fix the problem by
giving the source directory explicitly via an option provided by pbr.

Closes-Bug: #1502002
Change-Id: Ib17d53230e5a36a028438c0f2919f07c6013bfe2

commit_message:
Add versioning for cloud-init templates

Since cloud-init templates may vary from one release to another,
fuel-agent should be able to choose appropriate version according to
environment version provided in provision data.

Due to matter of changes, only boothook templates were affected,
the rest of templates haven't been changed yet.

* add templates from 6.1/stable
* add templates from 7.0/stable
* rename meta-data to meta_data

Change-Id: I03f9c304edb387435747c5f59d83516e8adcce9f
Closes-Bug: #1478549
Depends-On: I81b50863a58de10ee33c8064b38fc92ef7e1d86a

commit_message:
Improving GlanceStoreException

This code improves current implementation of base
store exception with several things:
1. default message shouldn't be an empty string
and has to provide some information.
2. __init__ has to accept position parameter with
message string to bring glance_store to conformity
with glance.
3. 'super' should use GlanceStoreException instead of
just Exception.

Note: This matches the behaviour of glance_store's exceptions
with glance's.

Co-authored-by: Mike Fedosin <mfedosin@mirantis.com>
Co-authored-by: Stuart McLaren <stuart.​mclaren@hp.​com>

Closes-bug: 1501443

Change-Id: I04d25874de1c0ec0c46d094c4d9144412e0ae5c9

commit_message:
Split up gate tests for LBaaSv2

The gate tests for LBaaSv2 take too long when using Octavia, so we need
to split up the tests into smaller chunks before Octavia becomes the ref
implementation, so things can actually pass the gate.
For the other side: I587d1b09accbc998e8f1a6e9ed9f84edb3a194a1

Change-Id: I9388ed0b17eb0b366cf0d85c2493b0ecfff32abf

commit_message:
Use requests in http check instead of urllib

The requests interface is much nicer and easier to
use so we might as well use it instead of direct urllib
usage.

Change-Id: I364ddb5f86900a3e166f4480d9f4889a68de247f

[{'created': '2015-10-05 15:14:21.000000000', 'message': 'rabbit: shuffle hosts before building kombu URL

This restores behavior as it was back in the Juno cycle.  This was
changed in a refactor during the Kilo cycle (973301aa) when the kombu
failover_strategy was set to shuffle.  But the failover_strategy only

commit_message:
rabbit: shuffle hosts before building kombu URL

This restores behavior as it was back in the Juno cycle.  This was
changed in a refactor during the Kilo cycle (973301aa) when the kombu
failover_strategy was set to shuffle.  But the failover_strategy only
affects failovers; it does not influence which host receives the
initial connection.

Thus, if multiple hosts are given, the first host will receive all of
the initial connections.  By shuffling the hosts before building the
URL given to kombu, rudimentary load balancing is achieved and
connections are more evenly spread across broker nodes.

Change-Id: Ieecaf5f286f49302db29df9854359ef5d36b7a89
(cherry picked from commit f2beb5eaf158f76cdb8be0ca72965503be423ee2)

commit_message:
add docstring to virt driver interface (as-is) [1 of ?]

The virt driver interface lacks documentation about preconditions and
postconditions as well as input and output parameters. This patch set
adds documentation to the current functionality "as-is". For this I
assumed that the libvirt driver, as the most used driver, should be
the source of truth. If the libvirt driver doesn't implement a method
I used the next driver which does (mostly XEN). If the driver didn't
provide information, I used the reaction and expectation from the
compute manager class in its role as user of the driver interface.

To keep this patch set assessable I will push other documentation
enhancements with following patch sets.

Change-Id: I7cad8dcb2a9b4a74cc71353ba4da14dd77528920

commit_message:
Various fixes for tempest tests with octavia

The octavia driver is now sending valid key values to octavia on listener and
pool updates.

Tempest tests are now appropriately waiting for the load balancer to become
active on many tests that made a change to the load balancer or its child but
did not wait for the load balancer to become active before making another
change to that load balancer or one of its children.

Change-Id: I0dce23401010b02a469d34e20adc22f020b83dbd

commit_message:
Remove dangling symlinks after node log removal

Dangling symlinks caused snapshots to generate without part of logs. The
symlinks were a leftover after deleteing logs from deleted nodes.

Existence of log folders was checked using os.path.exists function, it
was changed to os.path.lexists, which returns True for broken symlinks.

Change-Id: I446df0595ba668800e89f378ab08bd33cec4fb56
Closes-Bug: #1494838

commit_message:
Add a shade functional test for keystone v2

Our functional tests should work against both keystone v2 and keystone
v3. devstack now runs with both, so modify clouds.yaml to request v2
instead of v3.

Change-Id: Ie58af3e9eeca301fbf25e0170e011c9dd10235c2

commit_message:
Fix assign_vip for default admin network case

Default fuelweb_admin doesn't belong to any node group, so we can't use
the same SQL query to this network. So let's fallback to default admin
network in case there's no admin network in conroller's node group.

Closes-Bug: #1484181

Change-Id: I93034d9555b0851cf9c3d525cd7118de5a089dc3
Signed-off-by: Igor Kalnitsky <igor@kalnitsky.org>

commit_message:
Added snapshots list to volume views

Volume details view will contain list of snapshots named
as 'child_snapshots'.

Argument position of assertEqual method for related tests added.

Change-Id: I1e9cd9de34a039db2f0bfc24ee78864004c2c831
Closes-Bug: #1111839

Instance hostname is generated by displayname, currently, displayname can be
'----', and other Non-ASCII character such as Chinese characters,
sanitize_hostname will return empty in such cases.

This patch adds a helper function _default_host_name to give an instance
default name if sanitize_hostname returns empty hostname. And,
sanitize_hostname will truncated to 255 if the host name is too long.

Besides, added more test case to cover sanitize_hostname.

DocImpact
Change-Id: I443b51e0576cf657d96e498d6700bfc34d987301
Closes-Bug: #1495388

commit_message:
Give instance default hostname if hostname is empty

Instance hostname is generated by displayname, currently, displayname
can be '----', and other Non-ASCII character such as Chinese characters,
sanitize_hostname will return empty in such cases.

This patch adds a helper function _default_host_name to give an instance
default name if sanitize_hostname returns empty hostname. And,
sanitize_hostname will truncated to 63 if the host name is too long.

Also Window, Linux, and Dnsmasq have different limitation:

Windows: 255 (net_bios limit to 15, but window will truncate it)
Linux: 64
Dnsmasq: 63

Due to nova-network will leverage dnsmasq to set hostname, so we chose
63.

Besides, added more test cases to cover sanitize_hostname.

DocImpact
Change-Id: I443b51e0576cf657d96e498d6700bfc34d987301
Closes-Bug: #1495388
Co-authored-by: Alex Xu <hejie.xu@intel.com>

(2 comments)

Changing the views in the manner proposed here concerns me.

Currently, there are the following options for GETing one or more volumes:

1. A non-detailed volume query (ie, ?/volumes) which returns the "name", "id", and links for each volume
2. A detailed volume query (ie, /volumes/detail) which returns a lot of information for each volume
3. A volume-specific detailed query (ie, volumes/?{volume_id}?) which returns the same information as the the detailed volume query but only for a specific volume

If I understand this spec correctly, you are proposing to replace the output of non-detailed query (#1) with the current output of the detailed volume (#2) query? Is this correct? Won't this cause extra overhead and processing for REST API consumers that only want the non-detailed information?

Moreover, with this proposed change, won't all existing calls to the current detailed query (#2) automatically incur the extra overhead from always retrieving the child snaphots? In order to maintain the current behavior, anyone that is currently invoking #2 will need to change to #1.

It seems that the motivating use case for this spec is review [1] where the goal is to get the child snapshots when listing all volumes. Since do we not want to get the child snapshot information for every volume by default, did you consider adding an additional query string parameter to #2 above (ie, /volumes/detail?include_child_snapshots=1)? Or maybe only retrieve this information for the volume show API (#3)?

[1]: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/144739/'}, {'account_id': 1736, 'date': '2015-02-17 13:37:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

Steven,
You're right. I'm proposing to replace current '/v2/?{tenant_id}?/volumes' with '/v2/?{tenant_id}?/volumes/details' on the Rest API side since '/v2/?{tenant_id}?/volumes' is not used in python-cinderclient now.

Getting such lightweight API method as our current '/v2/?{tenant_id}?/volumes' could be useful, but I don't think that passing some additional data to from Cinder API will not raise a big performance impact.

If we'll return same data for 'volumes list' and 'volume get' would help us to work with volume objects returned from cinderclient in a single way. It's working now in a current python-cinderclient implementation.

Adding additional GET params for any properties (e.g. 'include_child_snapshots=1' for snapshots) makes our API and code much complex and I don't thinks that we need to go this way.

Anyway, if we'll need more light API we could implement something like '--minimal' param for client and Server API"}, {'account_id': 7198, 'date': '2015-02-17 17:18:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: -Code-Review

Right?  So, in the commit message you are proposing adding a --detailed parameter to enable getting detailed data back from the REST API request to /v2/{tenant_id}/volumes/ doesn't seem appropriate.

Maybe I just don't understand what you are proposing though.

Then as I start reading through this it seems that you are proposing to change what is returned for the default REST API request and detailed request.  This is where I get concerned.  cinderclient isn't the only consumer of of the REST API.  So changing the amount of detail coming from a request to"}, {'account_id': 1736, 'date': '2015-02-18 12:30:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

commit_message:
Volume get and list should be able get detailed views

Add '--detailed' param to 'cinder list' and 'cinder show' commands to
fetch all details about volumes including snapshots, backups, etc.

Blueprint: volume-details-views
Related-Bug: #1111839

Change-Id: I1ebce69f66ed738dfc22256d4a3fde07bbce198e

commit_message:
Added MAINTAINERS to top-level repo directory

In a consensus reached in a proposal for code review process
change [1], and proposed team structure policy document [2],
adding MAINTAINERS files in repositories.

Please note, that this file is written in YAML format in order
to allow further automation around code review process.

[1] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-August/072406.html
[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/225376/

Change-Id: I520d5285c2002818ce9e770d1fdc3265f9c36ebe

commit_message:
Convergence: Fix to persist stack status in DB

Due to recent code changes stack is marked complete/failed when
releasing the lock. But in case of convergence, stack lock is not
used.

Hence in case of convergence we need to still persist stack status
when state_set is called.

Change-Id: Ibe8c59a69e8dc8be3f0d15af238e166c852ab675
Closes-Bug: #1503296

commit_message:
Catch early devstack output into logfile

There is a fair bit that happens within devstack before it starts
writing out to the log-file (for example, reading all the
configuration to know that it needs to write to a log-file, for
example).  Capture this into log-files rather than /dev/null.

Change-Id: Iec2ad7b5598fdaefbc2338ade702bc7b08963b96

commit_message:
Dell Eqlx: Support over subscription in thin provisioning

Dell eqlx driver reports the following new stats:
  * provisioned_capacity
  * max_over_subscription_ratio
  * thin_provisioning_support (True or False)
  * thick_provisioning_support (True or False)

Change-Id: I09176259840eb5b52a5f4ec1942db2bf152667d0
Implements: blueprint dell-eqlx-over-subscription-thin-provisioning

commit_message:
Replace urllib(2), urlparse with six.moves.urllib

This change makes the modified code compatible with Python 3.

The initial patch was generated by the urllib operation of the sixer
tool. Changes on eventlet.green.urllib were reverted.

Co-Authored-By: janonymous <janonymous.codevulture@gmail.com>
Change-Id: Ie283c03305efd0e1da0e1406f721d619f12a5f1a

commit_message:
Fix Python 3 issues

* Replace basestring with six.string_types
* Replace dict.itervalues() with dict.values()
* Replace "raise a, b, c" with "six.reraise(a, b, c)"
* Replace unicode with six.text_type

The initial patch was generated by the basestring, raise and unicode
operations of the sixer tool.

Change-Id: I6948a5ffeddf086c2ea6e73e9aa11dfef2c081f5

commit_message:
Correct malformed argument to right type

In the Cloud Foundry in function $.setAttr(deployed, true) was used
'True' instead of 'true' which is wrong syntax for MuranoPL.

Change-Id: I95b2e07eb1a169f6464953427fb65e97bd3ef79c
Closes-Bug: #1504050
(cherry picked from commit 06d8b0a576a0478fce8858b7a5f2cb7db83549f4)

commit_message:
Revert "[libvirt] Move cleanup of imported files to imagebackend"

This reverts commit 9ba70756de326ffaa8be43acfde12cad04ed0af2

The change introduced an UnboundLocalError if we fail to
create the config_drive_image variable. Also, the original
change didn't have any unit tests and came late in the
liberty release so I don't really want to mess with fixing
this given we need the fix in liberty-rc2.

Change-Id: Ia7b70aa139b67cf58b5c0f9fbcd2a4deb465914e
Closes-Bug: #1502961

Split engine service test cases (11)

resources. During this refactoring, mox related calls are replaced by
mock calls.

commit_message:
remove corrupt get-pip.py

If get-pip servers fall over and return 503 for a few hours (which
they do medium regularly) we'll cache crud html, and everything will
suck. We know this script should be python, so if it isn't, delete it.

Change-Id: Ia9f6f7c7217939bc1ab5745f4a9d568acfbf04c8

commit_message:
Initial template2spec converter called tmpl2spec.py

This is a simple Jinja2 template parser with some distro
specific filters available. The current filters are:

- pypackname_normalize
  example: BuildRequires: {{ "Babel"  | pypackname_normalize }}
- license_normalize
  example: License: {{ "Apache-2.0" | license_normalize }}

Change-Id: Iec75393ca197e031ffebf0921e8471ddd3448ddf

commit_message:
Temporarily disable exception logging

We have encountered some weird errors when running tests for py34. The
LOG.exception() call is not working properly due to some unclear
reasons. This patch proposes a temporary patch to disable exception
logging. Will keep looking into the problem later.

Change-Id: I4c736d71272645c42b467fd7d8820e3c59c15118

commit_message:
Remove the not-implemented cinder store

We had a discussion about this on the mailing list and at the summit.
The conclusion of that discussion was that we should discuss a bit more
whether an implementation of this store is actually possible right now.

This patch removes the non-implemented cinder store and aims to kick off
this final discussion with regards to the feasability of this store.

Change-Id: I76d10c743bef7d7b850c81a9a5c35d7b89eb7c4d

commit_message:
Use ironic-python-agent as the default deploy ramdisk (WIP)

The bash ramdisk (created with deploy-ironic) is being deprecated in
Ironic. The ironic-python-agent deploy ramdisk is now the default deploy
ramdisk.

Change-Id: I379be94ce28afd38649019ebbb185ddb579c1a6b
Related-Blueprint: deprecate-bash-ramdisk

commit_message:
Fix 'Expected endpoint' error

Now, when input a command without os-image-api-version. The client
will raise an error: Expected endpoint.
The reason is that the 'auth_req' in
https://github.com/openstack/python-glanceclient/blob/master/glanceclient/shell.py#L449
will always be False.

Change-Id: I65a362abd9834489d60daf2d9075146c3b315568
Closes-bug: #1500677

commit_message:
rest: use a fork friendly app with werkzeug

Unlike many wsgi servers like apache mod_wsgi or uwsgi, werkzeug creates
the wsgi application object before forking workers.

This have some issues, storage/indexer connection are created
and leaves on the main process for no reason.
And the ceph storage driver just doesn't support to be
forked once the connection to ceph have been established.

This change creates a class that lazy load the application for
werkzeug and fixes these issues.

Closes-bug: #1499115

Change-Id: I398e289767e2e267466bcf882a5bb013620949d0

commit_message:
Increase visibility of the warning in autodoc files

Autogenerate-config-docs creates files that live in the
openstack-manuals repository, but are automatically generated
and should not be edited.

On occasion, contributors miss the warning not to edit the files.

This patch increases the previous warning so that it should take up
enough screen real-estate in a text editor that it would be less
easily skipped, and adds some additional information on what to do
instead.

Change-Id: I800e1ed19427e00f903046731fe8f22f22e4c6db

commit_message:
Added MAINTAINERS to top-level repo directory

In a consensus reached in a proposal for code review process
change [1], and proposed team structure policy document [2],
adding MAINTAINERS files in repositories.

Please note, that this file is written in YAML format in order
to allow further automation around code review process.

[1] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-August/072406.html
[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/225376/

Change-Id: I0090fb3f9bac3a15a28dc11671e8dce0edc2a94b

commit_message:
Removing fixed settings inside the glance-cache.conf

Using same overrides for the admin_user and admin_tenant_name
as the main glance API configuration.
This fix will make sure that the glance services will use the
same set of admin settings across multiple configuration files.

Change-Id: Ic3273848cd97aa17ae319fc8aec9ce77e2a9b1ba
Closes-Bug: #1503837

commit_message:
Skip bad meter definitions instead of erroring out

Currently we raise an exception once we hit a bad
meter definition in the yaml. Instead, skip the
bad ones and proceed with rest of the yaml.

Closes-Bug: #1503433

Change-Id: I1dd5b69bf9a92b5af5692ea75010f11a863b0afc

commit_message:
Allows the modification of the nova-api ports

In the api.pp manifest file, several new variables
have been added give the puppet-nova module an interface
for modifying several of the nova-api ports.

Change-Id: I47ca98a554f84855d55a648163f5498f51b33491
Closes-Bug: #1484402

commit_message:
Add methods for choise neutron segmentation for env

Currently all destructive neutron system tests are run only
with gre segmentation. In this patch added possibility for choice
neutron segmentation for these tests (vlan, vxlan, gre).
Each deployment configuration is defined in its own class.
Common functionality for these classes is implemented
in base (parent) class. After merging this patch test group
'ha_neutron_destructive_2' will be removed and replaced
with three new groups: "ha_neutron_destructive_vlan" ,
"ha_neutron_destructive_gre" and "ha_neutron_destructive_vxlan".

Change-Id: Ia8c8d8fb50a438da8a61d0cbc153f1ae03143ffd
Closes-bug: #1471272

Fix keystone::auth class example

The documented example omitted the password parameter, which is
required. This patch fixes the documentation.

Change-Id: If95d821cd59ab62f573147a7c25c7bc93d2f9b76

commit_message:
Add test of claim context manager abort

Removes the successful-path unit test of the instance claim context
manager out of test_resource_tracker because there is no difference in
the code paths between the use of the context manager successfully and
using the claim object directly. Adds a new unit test to the
test_tracker that verifies the claim.abort() method is called when an
exception is raised during the claim object acting as a context manager.

Change-Id: I98724e1e58dfc5320ee672f48f072472bee26f4e

[{'created': '2015-10-07 03:29:25.000000000', 'message': "Don't set xtrace directly in local call

Ia0957b47187c3dcadd46154b17022c4213781112 detects setting local
variables with subshell commands.

Although this is a particuarly benign case, it trips the test.  Rather
than putting in an ignore for this, we can easily change it to make
the test pass.  This seems better than putting in special work-arounds
to bashate, etc.

commit_message:
Don't set xtrace directly in local call

Ia0957b47187c3dcadd46154b17022c4213781112 detects setting local
variables with subshell commands.

Although this is a particuarly benign case, it trips the test.  Rather
than putting in an ignore for this, we can easily change it to make
the test pass.  This seems better than putting in special work-arounds
to bashate, etc.

Change-Id: I37c3967c0f2d780a636a7d26cda83755085c5c69

We should add the foreign key constraint integrity error to the warning
since it includes detailed information about the reference table that
caused the constraint failure, which is useful for knowing things are
out of order without having to check your database.

You get something like this now:

2015-10-07 15:29:38.238 WARNING nova.db.sqlalchemy.api
[req-6115aef5-2a82-4d42-bf67-eaab2e8eee63 None None] IntegrityError
 detected when archiving table instances: (pymysql.err.IntegrityError)
 (1451, u'Cannot delete or update a parent row: a foreign key constraint

 REFERENCES `instances` (`uuid`))') [SQL: u'DELETE FROM instances WHERE

"}]
commit_message:
Log DBReferenceError in archive_deleted_rows_for_table

We should add the foreign key constraint integrity error to the warning
since it includes detailed information about the reference table that
caused the constraint failure, which is useful for knowing things are
out of order without having to check your database.

You get something like this now:

2015-10-07 15:29:38.238 WARNING nova.db.sqlalchemy.api
[req-6115aef5-2a82-4d42-bf67-eaab2e8eee63 None None] IntegrityError
 detected when archiving table instances: (pymysql.err.IntegrityError)
 (1451, u'Cannot delete or update a parent row: a foreign key constraint
 fails (`nova`.`instance_actions`, CONSTRAINT
 `fk_instance_actions_instance_uuid` FOREIGN KEY (`instance_uuid`)
 REFERENCES `instances` (`uuid`))') [SQL: u'DELETE FROM instances WHERE
 instances.id in (SELECT T1.id FROM (SELECT instances.id \nFROM
 instances \nWHERE instances.deleted != %s ORDER BY instances.id \n
 LIMIT %s) as T1)'] [parameters: (0, 10)]

Related-Bug: #1183523

Change-Id: I41b10898c6e9cc48da58c4d2daf7df362fc9fc36

Hi Paul,

The OVS driver and the data path switch need to know whether a SF is L2 type or L3 type in order to program the switch's flow forwarding table properly so that a flow packet can be properly forwarded to the SF. For example, the forwarding rule on the switch is different if it is a "L2 insertion type" SF from if it is a "L3 insertion type" SF. This "insertion type" info is determined by the SF itself (e.g. there are L2 FW and L3 FW) and need to be passed down to the driver from the API layer so that the driver and data path implementation can properly steer the flow packet to the desired SF.'}, {'account_id': 14605, 'date': '2015-08-19 05:18:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

commit_message:
Use DBReferenceError in archive_deleted_rows_for_table

There is an old TODO in here to switch from the generic DBError to
DBReferenceError, which was added to oslo.db in commit a9e3af2eb back in
the 0.4.0 release so we're safe to use this now.

Change-Id: Ifb3d8890827a6bbc782c15b6d4fd3902dbb5dacf

commit_message:
Remove unused context parameter from db.archive_deleted_rows* methods

Commit 316a94dd03c0206e05e7dd8962fcc0b41340d8ca removed the usage of
the @require_admin_context decorator from the DB API methods and the
context parameter was only used for that decorator, so we can remove
the context parameter now.

Change-Id: Ib55b69c5bf00957e26f728892b3c842e9bab7b2f

commit_message:
Add retries to ssh._get_hosts_name_for_node

It is possible for ssh._get_hosts_name_for_node to return None when
the driver is not able to find a VM corresponding to given MAC
addresses or when incorrect information about nodes is returned by
SSH call to VM manager. In the latter case _get_hosts_name_for_node
should be retried.

This adds two new configs to the [ssh] group:
 - 'get_vm_name_attempts': number of attempts to try to get VM name
   corresponding to a node's MAC address
 - 'get_vm_name_retry_interval': time (secs) to wait between
   attempts to get VM name

Closes-bug: #1493748

Change-Id: I0457113d57f82cccc5cb353123fb087f6ba63aa2

commit_message:
Update for openstackdocstheme 1.2.3

Require new version and cleanup conf.py, we do no need pwd variable
anymore.

Also update requirement for openstack-doc-tools, 0.30 is current minimum
version.

[Contributor Guide] Reviewing documentation

This patch:

* Translates the below page to RST:
  https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Documentation/HowTo#Reviewing_Documentation
* Restructures the section linking to the existing content in the
  Infra manual and wiki pages.
* Removes old outdated content.

Implements: blueprint docs-contributor-guide

[{'created': '2015-10-07 21:46:59.000000000', 'message': "Move deprecation warnings higher up in the cmd callstack

Whilst the builtin open method is mocked during tests,
some utilities (like debtcollector) may still rely on the
real thing. This can cause intermittent failures due to
the concurrent nature of of the test execution.

This is particularly true during the execution of test_migration
tests, where the deprecation message ends up being called while
the open method is mocked.

This patch works around the issue by ensuring that, when the
debcollector's method is called, we are outside the mock context
and hence open() is indeed the authentic one.

Closes-bug: #1503847

Change-Id: Ibdc89a8b6a05d9f4fac916b519f6dc9340f4a080
"}]
commit_message:
Move deprecation warnings higher up in the cmd callstack

Whilst the builtin open method is mocked during tests,
some utilities (like debtcollector) may still rely on the
real thing. This can cause intermittent failures due to
the concurrent nature of of the test execution.

This is particularly true during the execution of test_migration
tests, where the deprecation message ends up being called while
the open method is mocked.

This patch works around the issue by ensuring that, when the
debcollector's method is called, we are outside the mock context
and hence open() is indeed the authentic one.

Closes-bug: #1503847

Change-Id: Ibdc89a8b6a05d9f4fac916b519f6dc9340f4a080

commit_message:
Add traceback error

This patch adds the traceback error to be emmitted to the stderr when
Kuryr catches the exceptions for making debugging easier.

Change-Id: I74c6dc8c075c06f3fe3b9508e2dc5f523196b795

Hi jichenjc,

There are still some cases where unnecessary bdm entries will be created in db.

e.g., If you send two requests simultaneously to call attach volume, both the calls will pass "check_attach" because at that time volume is in "available" status and will create bdm entries in db. Later when call reaches to compute manager, only one thread can access the "do_attach_volume" method at a time. In this case first request will update volume status to "in-use" and the other will cause failure and will destroy the bdm which will remain unused in the block_device_mapping table.'}, {'account_id': 6062, 'date': '2015-03-26 17:15:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

sorry but I didn't fully understand here ...

if both thread pass the status check , then we will still
call reserve_block_device_name and assign device for each request 
so the second thread will still got another reservation 
and failed to attach later will only remove that reservation

what's the side effect then? 

thanks a lot"}, {'account_id': 10485, 'date': '2015-03-30 07:12:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Hi jichenjc,

As you mentioned above that second thread will still got another reservation and will remove it on failure. That means this second bdm is unnecessarily created and destroyed, which is we are trying to fix in this bug.

commit_message:
Avoid create / destory db info if volume attached

Nova will reserve a device name before attach volume,
however, if the volume is already attached, the
reservation will be destroyed. Acutally the check
attach can be done prior to reserve block device name
so no addtional db access is needed.

Checked commit e4475116 and 339a97d0, seems none of them
fixed a race condition on purpose.
Also, seems code is straight forward so no unit test are added.

Change-Id: I7b2ae6b53392ccdf0e28c2cc9b31b701b250ba4a
Closes-Bug: #1427060

commit_message:
Replace deprecated tempest config option

In patch https://review.openstack.org/#/c/211601/13
config sections in tempest for admin authentication
become deprecated and if we need to get an admin username
we can't find it in identity section anymore.

This patch replaces identity config section call to auth
in tempest_utils.py

Change-Id: I9a0d07009c9fe8e46066c50c05fa1fa5263bc84e
Closes-Bug: #1503764

commit_message:
Remove Cirros URL from IMAGE_URLS

Devstack introduced DOWNLOAD_DEFAULT_IMAGES setting which
by default is True and extends IMAGE_URLS variable with
some default images, including Cirros. devstack-vagrant
also extends IMAGE_URLS with Cirros URL. This results in
error about duplicate entries in this variable.

Change-Id: I86f1ca5b9bef73e41657ce6fec17dd378d9e33ef
Closes-Bug: #1497533

Tests from `nova.tests.unit.api.openstack.test_common` are broken in
Python 3 environment since range function doesn't return a list object as
in Python 2.
Since list objects are expected only in assertEqual methods to check empty
ranges, we can check length of returned object.

* https://docs.python.org/3/library/functions.html#func-range

Change-Id: I025bbb66d5446c76d89ef086dcd12a2a454b0e31
"}]
commit_message:
[Py34] nova.tests.unit.api.openstack.test_common

Tests from `nova.tests.unit.api.openstack.test_common` are broken in
Python 3 environment since range function doesn't return a list object as
in Python 2.
Since list objects are expected only in assertEqual methods to check empty
ranges, we can check length of returned object.

* https://docs.python.org/3/library/functions.html#func-range

Change-Id: I025bbb66d5446c76d89ef086dcd12a2a454b0e31

commit_message:
Use StrOpt's parameter choices to restritct option auth_strategy

oslo.config provides value check for StrOpt with parameter choices.
And we use option auth_strategy directly without any check like:
 limit_name = CONF.auth_strategy + '_nolimit'
So we'd better restrict its value in keystone and noauth2.

Change-Id: I782c493d43fcdd27c3d6660cbb2800c90fbbd980

commit_message:
Functional tests: Use a configurable url pattern

This removes the append_version_to_url config option in favor of
a pattern that will build the request url by interpolating arguments.

Change-Id: I0b1152d518a5f4ddfcfc5d5a7b28606932a86c4b

commit_message:
Clear out pyc files before a tox run

When switching back from master to a stable branch, tests
will often fail as pyc files will exist for migrations
that no longer have py files.

Change-Id: Ie3d892f86b929e87605ba29f4237152c4a47bec8

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC

commit_message:
Change 'Quantum server' to 'Neutron server'

In Admin-Cloud-Guide, Networking Section, Scalable and highly available
DHCP agents subsection, the figure shows the structure of three hosts with
Neutron configuration. In Controller node, it still shows "Quantum
server", but it is replaced by "Neutron server" now.

Change-Id: I692c7edb150f78087d96110facd4a76565ef9360
Closes-bug: #1503976

commit_message:
Added MAINTAINERS to top-level repo directory

In a consensus reached in a proposal for code review process
change [1], and proposed team structure policy document [2],
adding MAINTAINERS files in repositories.

Please note, that this file is written in YAML format in order
to allow further automation around code review process.

[1] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-August/072406.html
[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/225376/

Change-Id: If2baa1952cc692bd66dc4427104763900d96cc22

commit_message:
Use mount -t sysfs to avoid host /sys dependencies

This patch updates the _install_grub2 function in image.py
so that we use 'mount -t sysfs' instead of bind mounting
the hosts /sys into the chroot.

This resolves issues which can occur with unmounting
the chroot mounts where 'target is busy' errors
may occur when you are debugging things with a serial
console.

Change-Id: I5c9a6546d048cbf54695329d9744fda55127bd30
Closes-bug: #1503385

commit_message:
Make non-admin user package Tenant Name more clear

Now non-admin use 'other' instead for non-user tenant.
But in some case 'other' maybe use as the tenant name,
So we need make it more clear. Use 'UNKNOWN' for it.

Change-Id: I461679aeceecb46a5d550122e45d064e8f7dadda
Closes-Bug: #1502902

commit_message:
Added MAINTAINERS to top-level repo directory

In a consensus reached in a proposal for code review process
change [1], and proposed team structure policy document [2],
adding MAINTAINERS files in repositories.

Please note, that this file is written in YAML format in order
to allow further automation around code review process.

[1] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-August/072406.html
[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/225376/

OK, looking more deeply into this issue, I don't believe this patch is the correct approach to the problem. It's masking an error down in the nova API code by fudging the data up in our view layer.

The data in the view layer should be allowed to be unicode. The data should instead be encoded at the point of calling into the API.

What I'm saying is that this is a bug in novaclient, not Horizon. This patch simply masks it (and not even completely, as is noted in the commit message)."}, {'account_id': 12071, 'date': '2015-09-17 00:54:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

And just so we're clear: by "the data should be allowed to be unicode" I *explicitly* mean Python unicode objects, not utf-8 encoded strings. The encoding of unicode objects to byte strings should be done at the interface between our code and the outside world, not internally in our code as this patch proposes. That means in the OpenStack API clients, or in the HTML rendering and HTTP request handling (and Django already does this for us).'}, {'account_id': 12071, 'date': '2015-09-17 05:34:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

I have proposed fixes to novaclient and nova for this issue.'}, {'account_id': 12071, 'date': '2015-09-17 05:34:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

References would be a good idea, sorry :)

novaclient https://review.openstack.org/#/c/224422/
nova https://review.openstack.org/#/c/224431/'}, {'account_id': 12826, 'date': '2015-09-18 13:34:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

Judging by the comments and other fixes, this patch could be abandoned now.'}, {'account_id': 10442, 'date': '2015-09-18 13:36:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

yes, rob.
i will do it now.
please make this bug invalid in launchpad.'}, {'account_id': 12826, 'date': '2015-10-08 09:51:02.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Abandoned as per discussion in comments.'}]

commit_message:
filter doesn't handle unicode character

In server side filters, if we include unicode character
in the search string, it is throwing 'UnicodeEncodeError'.

To avoid this error the sting should be encoded in
utf-8 format.

This patch encoding the search string to utf-8 to
avoid the UnicodeEncodeError.

Note: Still nova and glance client is not handling
the unicode character but this patch makes sure
that the horizon providing the proper encoded
string to the client.

Change-Id: I87b55fa57dc5976a39ac4d55d702665471447937
Closes-Bug: #1472999

commit_message:
Update the murano agent README

Delete the extra ‘\’ in
--property murano_image_info='{"title": "Ubuntu for Murano", \
  "type": "linux"}'

Otherwise it will cause Error:the Invalid metadata for image.

Change-Id: I305672d709769acfd781f3b6d11489ff567c2ab6

commit_message:
Documentation: Syntax checking before running playbooks

This brings:
1) A new page to explain how can a deployer test its
configuration files.

2) Links on the pages mentionning the playbooks that
traditionally has errors because of the deployer's config.

Change-Id: I434152a14de806e24e5886969dfa15e3ff1c4928

commit_message:
Fix images no attribute type and title error

Images have no attribute type and title gives the error like:
The attribute type doesn't exist on <Image {u'status': u'active',
u'properties': {u'murano_image_info': u'{"title": "Ubuntu for Murano", \\\n "type": "linux"}'},
...u'id': u'4ceb8c90-c13e-466d-b5cc-a69a8590e331', u'size': 13200896}>.
The attribute title doesn't exist on <Image {u'status': u'active',
u'properties': {u'murano_image_info': u'{"title": "Ubuntu for Murano", \\\n "type": "linux"}'},
...u'id': u'4ceb8c90-c13e-466d-b5cc-a69a8590e331', u'size': 13200896}>.

Change-Id: I2ac9204f00a25a999127217ef95a38ec5b3e71ac
Closes-bug: #1503993

commit_message:
add pylint in tox pep8 task

This change updates tox.ini so that the pep8 jobs
does a pylint check of the source code.

This the same as done in many other projects, in particular
.pylintrc is based on the one in neutron.

Change-Id: Ib46cb485345896c4f5eabd3b1d705200b0640963
Depends-On: I0cab12f2775f4f803d2eeee4cc6d6f06da5d4b7a

Add missing config option for service broker

Add 'enabled' flag for service broker API. It can be used in DevStack
and other automatic deployments.

Change-Id: I7ef350f20d1a5a24418897eeec8ddae2f2a743a3
Closes-Bug: #1502910

commit_message:
Fix creating policy with long abbreviation fails

When we create policy with long abbreviation that more than
5 chars, like: "test_abbr", DB exception is raised, because
"abbreviation" column length is 5 in policy table, and that
cause inconsistency between database and policy engine,
because when database exception issue, policy engine don't
rollback the policy. This patch fixes the issue.

Change-Id: I6343d06be66c76cd0433114e2a5add9a56392a6b
Closes-Bug: #1497881

Improve network group validation

The validation for creating network groups and updating
them has been split into two independent methods. This
This change also prevents a network group's nodegroup from
being changed.

commit_message:
puppet: allow to configure any ceilometer param with Hiera

By including ::ceilometer::config on controller & compute, we allow
anyone to trick ceilometer.conf with any parameter, using Hiera.

Change-Id: Ie6698d5e6900ecaaf7f19ed79e9c44b39ced0559

commit_message:
devstack: stop using USE_CONSTRAINTS and setup_package

Change I843208e2e982eb04931b76f5cb4bd219fbcd70de in devstack removed the
usage of USE_CONSTRAINTS entirely without any warning. That means every
pip installed packaged is now forced to honor global requirements.

Now the gate is broken because the upper-constraint from
openstack/requirement build the wheel for pandas with the wrong version
etc. Since we just don't want to be bothered with that repository, we
have to bypass devstack usual setup function.

Change-Id: I4988f41e21c8efd15f3f619cff9abfd5fd39ea79

Python3: Fix Remaining issues of python3 compatibility in bin directory

Changes Of py3 in bin :

* https://review.openstack.org/#/c/196835/
* ConfigParser from six.moves

Change-Id: Ic0374c8e09dfd595ec12c4d31b17dad30eaa803c

subject: Python 3 using builtins instead of __builtin__, rename raw_input() to input() from six.moves

This patch doesn't work for me and breaks:

http://paste.openstack.org/show/376712/

Looks like six.moves.builtins.input uses input() on Py2:

 from six.moves import builtins
 >>> builtins.input('y/n: ')
 y/n: y
 Traceback (most recent call last):
   File "<stdin>", line 1, in <module>
   File "<string>", line 1, in <module>
 NameError: name 'y' is not defined
 >>> help(builtins.input)
 Help on built-in function input in module __builtin__:

 input(...)
     input([prompt]) -> value
    
     Equivalent to eval(raw_input(prompt)).'}, {'account_id': 6968, 'date': '2015-07-15 07:37:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)

OK, found the reason. You have to import from six.moves, not from six.moves.builtins:

 from six.moves import input

That uses raw_input in Py2:

 >>> from six.moves.builtins import input
 >>> input.__name__
 'input'
 >>> from six.moves import input
 >>> input.__name__
 'raw_input'"}, {'account_id': 14867, 'date': '2015-07-15 14:46:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)

commit_message:
Python 3 using builtins instead of __builtin__, rename raw_input() to input() from six.moves

Using these modules from six

Replacements:
*input() from six.moves could be used instead of raw_input()
*__builtin__ with six.moves.builtins

Change-Id: I8749dd33496ed8718bd2c6620c9dc5240c2ce683

commit_message:
Set resource status to FAILED when engine is down

When resource is in status IN_PROGRESS and engine service
went down, user can't operate(such as update) the resource
anymore even if the engine service is back again.
This patch set the resources to FAILED status when
the engine starting.

Change-Id: Ib49895d45d727e117af5dbdcf84d58b196991274
Closes-Bug: #1487288
(cherry picked from commit fae9ae327fbd9f1bfb1d6301a49b780e7a9192cd)

commit_message:
Bump upper constraints for keystoneclient and keystonemiddleware

We recently released new versions of these libraries in time for
liberty, we should change them for master and backport

Change-Id: I21a72ce090aecb58dfac6426f98026edccf4cbaa

commit_message:
Remove "extensions" from volumes_extensions_client

Many Nova APIs are extensions and it is meaningless to contain
the word "extensions" in service client names.
Then this patch removes the word before migrating the service
client to tempest-lib.

Change-Id: Ibd9b6c67c5b9790b6d6f1a76d334ee5d6c98ad5f

This works, I guess. But we've already added matches for cloudos in devstack and system-config, so not sure why this would be the odd-one out

I'm trying to think of something that just matches everything we're interested in.  Just detecting /usr/bin/rpm doesn't seem to work; it *could* be installed on debian/ubuntu.  searching for yum also isn't right for fedora22+ and suse

However, I think that checking the return of "rpm -qf /etc/*-release" would do the right thing here in basically every case?  Every system uses rpm underneath, all ship a release file (cloudos, orcalelinux, centos, suse, fedora) and all ultimately use rpm (even given yum/dnf/zypper differences)?

I might just throw this idea into the CI and see what happens'}, {'account_id': 7118, 'date': '2015-09-22 19:54:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

commit_message:
Third-party rhel-based oses in devstack-gate

By this patch we allow third-party vendors to run CIs on OSes
which are unsupported by upstream devstack-gate,
and could be regarded as Fedora in a reasonable sense.

We need it to support CloudLinux, which is a commercial RHEL-based distribution
aimed specifically at web-hosting usage.
You may read about more: https://www.cloudlinux.com/about/compatibility.php

Change-Id: I77957e9a107f0b1aeef81fb6a98e9840954d2a44
Depends-On: I01285d92d823b5e4fb4943bc31ff3ec6361eb5a2

I'm not sure this should be fixed in openstack-ansible.
IIRC, it's best to fix the problems upstream instead of growing openstack-ansible with workarounds.
I'm afraid this fix could be forgotten in the repo, and will not be updated when the upstream fix will be available.

Moreover, IIRC, next tagged version of spice doesn't include any fix related to this issue, so it seems a more "long term" issue.

FYI, in our deployment, with added this kind of fix outside of openstack-ansible, and documented how we fixed it in the bug report.'}, {'account_id': 14805, 'date': '2015-09-23 15:44:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

It has been fixed upstream and, I agree, that's where anything like this should be corrected.
Whenever there is a package available that contains the fix, this change should definitely be removed and replaced with an upgrade to that package.

In the meantime, there's a configuration option that's essentially broken and I don't think asking each deployer to discover that and then maintain their own fix for it is acceptable.

https://github.com/SPICE/spice-html5/commit/293d405e15a4499219fe81e830862cc2b1518e3e"}, {'account_id': 14805, 'date': '2015-09-23 16:59:10.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-09-23 18:43:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

Sorry Jimmy -- but I think I prefer your original solution.  Obviously, I don't think it's ideal modifying packaged files but I think that's the lesser evil to doing a 'make install' on a host.  The latter means we have untracked cruft on the host which may cause all sorts of issues somewhere down the line.

I'd like to hear more opinions here before we merge/re-update this review."}, {'account_id': 6816, 'date': '2015-09-25 09:14:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

@Matt on the one hand I agree, but on the other hand carrying a patch is also evil. Perhaps this method can be adjusted to use the source, but install differently? It seems like Ubuntu/spice-html5 don't do package updates very often so the source-based build is very advantageous for picking up improvements."}, {'account_id': 6816, 'date': '2015-09-25 09:15:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Also note that the bug related to this was registered a long time ago and we've been hoping for an upstream fix instead of having to carry a patch."}, {'account_id': 14805, 'date': '2015-09-25 19:15:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

The 'make install' looks intimidating, but in this case it's just a copy of html, css, and js files from the cloned folder to /usr/share/spice-html5
https://github.com/SPICE/spice-html5/blob/spice-html5-0.1.6/Makefile#L68

I think going directly to the git repo may be better long-term.
Like Jesse mentioned, Ubuntu has been slow to create a new package and we'd be able to pick up fixes for other things more quickly like whenever this patch gets included https://bugs.launchpad.net/ubuntu/+source/spice-html5/+bug/1423669"}, {'account_id': 7353, 'date': '2015-09-28 01:30:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

I'm in favor of this change as its going to source which will maintain sustainability and capability. Like Matt, I too believe cloning directly into place would be better and would not require the call to "make". I have a similar review in progress to implement novnc support via the upstream git source. I'd like to see the sources cloned directly into the repo server infrastructure and distributed from their. The following are a few examples of where I'd like to see this type of change go:

commit_message:
Install spice-html5 from source

'ws://' is currently hardcoded within the spice_auto.html file included
in the packaged release of spice-html5, raising a security error when
accessing consoles over HTTPS.

Remove the existing apt package and install spice-html5 from source
instead since this issue has been corrected as of spice-html5-0.1.6.

Change-Id: Ie308a477143037963f903f2ac21b2b1f0328fcb3
Partial-Bug: #1424797

commit_message:
Add novnc console support

This change adds in support for the novnc console type in Nova.

* The change adds in a few new variables to the defaults which allow
  for the novnc console to be configued.
* A port entry was added to haproxy to support the console type.
* noVNC is being installed from source in the nova_console container.
  The git repo has been added to the openstack_other.yml repo-package file
  which allows for the repo to be cloned into the repo containers and then
  distributed out where needed from within the environment.

Closes-Bug: 1428833

Change-Id: I221557aad77bf266b4e2fae23007ffa210aa1f75
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
Added LC_ALL to openrc

This commit adds the LC_ALL export to the openrc file to ensure that
the openstack clients and system work with different preset local
settings.

Change-Id: I9f62b9b3db50b70ebdddc724215ebd3b0a138e42
Closes-Bug: #1408935

I'd rather see the docs change included with this review. It's a small enough review that I don't think it will hold the review up much. Further, we should link to http://www.openbsd.org/cgi-bin/man.cgi/OpenBSD-current/man5/ssh_config.5?query=ssh%5fconfig&sec=5 (or something similar) for instructions so that users can increase it.

That said, perhaps we should be a bit more dynamic about the way we determine the MaxSessions for this library so that when users increase that, they don't also need to manually specify it here. That is clearly better for a different patch though so we can get this (arguably better) default in sooner rather than later."}, {'account_id': 6816, 'date': '2015-10-02 14:18:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Workflow-1

commit_message:
Limit the number of Ansible forks used to 10

The default MaxSessions setting for SSHD is 10. Each Ansible fork makes use of
a Session, so this patch still uses the CPU number to set the number of forks
used but limits it to 10 forks when the number of CPU's is larger.

Developer Docs and Install Guide Docs entries have been included.

Closes-Bug: #1479812
Change-Id: I9abd33e184c706796ede9963393876a8aae9837c

commit_message:
Support creating profile from yaml and file

Profile examples: https://github.com/stackforge/senlin/tree/master/examples/profiles

Delete the profile creating unit test and will add them in next patch.

We do not check anything in form.clean(), leave the checking in backend.

Change-Id: I64672a4f8c45ce852860c537ee194f94736e37a7

commit_message:
Update Dev Quick-Start links to officail docs

Moved all Dev Quick-Start realted documents to docs/source folder
(html files will be genrated for them at
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/magnum),
Updated all Dev Quick-Start interanl links to
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/magnum, converted Mesos cluster
with Heat to rst (requred for docs)

Change-Id: Ibba5f44fc5ce9cab30adc0957b6103c811329a06

commit_message:
Added MAINTAINERS to top-level repo directory

In a consensus reached in a proposal for code review process
change [1], and proposed team structure policy document [2],
adding MAINTAINERS files in repositories.

Please note, that this file is written in YAML format in order
to allow further automation around code review process.

[1] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-August/072406.html
[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/225376/

Change-Id: I4ede55c66831a07779f45869ebdd7119e254e580

commit_message:
Enable agent_ilo for uefi-bios switching

Closes-bug: #1412559

Adds ability for the agent_ilo driver to switch modes
from UEFI to BIOS and vice-versa.

Change-Id: I3e8f853d0b044da3c25c17e415097a0f2ae40df2

commit_message:
Generate report at the end of rally-dsvm job

Seems like report can't be generated in 100% cases. Sometimes
it crashes with such message:

 RallyException: Unable to calculate the mean: no values processed so far.

It makes sense to genereate report after we get raw results, so it will
be possible to debug such cases locally.

Change-Id: I6d93617dfaf6d954a85b1428f828f7b57f6b6212

commit_message:
Added MAINTAINERS to top-level repo directory

In a consensus reached in a proposal for code review process
change [1], and proposed team structure policy document [2],
adding MAINTAINERS files in repositories.

Please note, that this file is written in YAML format in order
to allow further automation around code review process.

[1] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-August/072406.html
[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/225376/

Change-Id: I0a52944ad322405989a7e403312f04c6a11853c2

commit_message:
[install] Liberty updates for swift

Update swift configuration for Liberty. Includes moving
basic host configuration of object storage nodes to
environment section. Also addresses some consistency
issues, mostly from the RST conversion.

Changes and testing specific to distribution packages
primarily involve Ubuntu. Other distributions may require
additional patches.

Change-Id: I00c9f9fbc3700ebf0423a4c1ac92ff6863852df6
Implements: blueprint installguide-liberty

With any luck, we'll be able to call a direct-transfer method on new libvirt versions (or version which backport the function), and fall back to stream --> python --> stream for current or older versions.  Once we make a bit of progress on that, I can update the blueprint.  I'm thinking that I should implement the initial version without waiting for any new function, and then add a new commit afterwards to integrate the new function when available. [{'created': '2014-04-08 01:06:38.000000000', 'message': 'Blueprint to use libvirt storage pools

This blueprint proposes using libvirt storage pools for storing local

commit_message:
Blueprint to migrate libvirt volumes

This blueprint proposes using built-in libvirt volume transfer
methods to transfer libvirt volumes between compute nodes,
in order to facilitate cold migrations and resizes.

Spec for blueprint migrate-libvirt-volumes

Change-Id: I99ff6cbd59592ef2d694984e6babd52c549dc295

commit_message:
Remove compose from the repostiory since its dead code

Several people over the liberty cycle committed to maintaining
compose, but it was never completed.  Rather than carry compose
in our repoistory until the end of time in a broken state I propose
removing it.  If someone comes along and wants to resseruct the code
and make it functional in the future, I'd be 100% open to merge a
patch in the future which reintroduces this functionality.  In the
meantime it is confusing to users which ask me on a daily basis if
compose is supported which I have to go into a 10 minute monologue
about why its in the repository.

Fortunately git contains full history so we can always revert this
change at a later time if someone wants to actually fixt his code
base up and make it useable in some way.  I think the proper answer
is a seperate repoistory (kolla-compose) which contains any compose
related bits.

Please consider removing since nobody is using this code and its
dead.

TrivialFix

backport: liberty
Change-Id: I8b7c39b00d1967184d363af7db86d1ff8b5e725f

commit_message:
Configure CoreOS for Kubernetes load balancer feature

Kubernetes service provides the LoadBalancer feature

This is supported through an OpenStack plugin in Kubernetes code.
Enabling this feature requires configuring the cluster properly for
Kubernetes to interface with Neutron.  Kubernetes backend will then
create the Neutron load balancer pool, members, VIP and monitor,
and manage the pool members as pods are added/removed from the
service.

This patch updates the CoreOS heat templates for host name and
network name that match what Kubernetes code expects.
The scripts used by these templates are in the patch for Fedora Atomic
which this patch has a dependency on.

Partially-Implements: blueprint external-lb
Change-Id: I9b927624968a463625f399e0fc5deec2c6173e5f

commit_message:
Release version 1.0.0

Our current version based upon conversations with TTX was
0.1.0. It appears now that the full API is nearly stable.  It is
stable enough to call our first Liberty release 1.0.0.

The API consists of the following data:
The locations of config files passed to the container
The environment variables expected by the container
The JSON encoded file containing the copy and cmd operations

Each container in current master follows the same sytnax and
style for all of the implementations of every container that
atleast has been Ansibilized.

backport: liberty

Change-Id: I2064689ca6fd9f332ad26624e1b93f6aaa08e79b
Closes-Bug: #1503494

update doc about local registry in image-building

Reformat local registry section. And document that the Docker config need to
be modified when building images if using local registry.

Remove explicit support for OneConvergence plugin

This is being removed from the Neutron tree, so there is
no need to keep it here anymore.

commit_message:
Port swob to Python 3

* HeaderEnvironProxy: replace UserDict.DictMixin with
  collections.MutableMapping, add __iter__ and __len__ methods, and
  add more unit tests
* Replace url* imports with six.moves.urllib

Change-Id: I9ed22d0dd52ee7ac8fa16571f82c45975cfdffff

commit_message:
build_docs: do not handle md and conf files with shocco

At the moment the following md and conf files are handled with shocco.
This should not be the case.

* samples/local.conf
* lib/neutron_thirdparty/README.md
* lib/neutron_plugins/README.md

Change-Id: I11ea5ebda111e6cdab71d3cffaeb4f16443bfd3c

commit_message:
fix warning in install_get_pip

we were unconditionally adding -z to the curl command even if the file
doesn't exist that we are referencing. That produces a scary warning
for users. Lets not do that.

Change-Id: Id2860c1c702510b0f8fd496abce579d0fa3ff867

commit_message:
add big warning for extras.d usage

This adds a warning for extras.d usage. This will give us something to
keep an eye on in logstash to build up the list of projects that will
break at Mitaka-1.

This also makes the deprecated handling done through a function, which
will hopefully make it more consistent in the future.

Change-Id: Icd393bc3e7095fe58be0fd13ef74fece3aa5c5f1

commit_message:
Add Barbican to plugin registry list

Barbican can now be installed with devstack via:

enable_plugin barbican https://git.openstack.org/openstack/barbican

Change-Id: I81af04bb6600d1e58590c39efdc2c0c91563321d

commit_message:
Add a moved function helper

This is useful for moving functions to newer names
or newer modules/locations and retaining the old function
so that the old function proxies to the new function and
emits a deprecation warning when it is called.

Also fixes how the 'get_callable_name' needs to filter
for none, as it appears that when ran under sphinx the
'__module__' attribute is set to none and this causes
issues when joining into a string.

Change-Id: I290f1b71c141c6647da1750aec348ea590a8d9bd

commit_message:
Document httpd for accept on /identity, /identity_admin

Apache Httpd can be configured to accept keystone requests on all
sorts of interfaces. The sample config file is updated to show
how to configure Apache Httpd to also send requests on /identity
and /identity_admin to keystone.

Closes-Bug: 1496041
Change-Id: Ie7b829eff16c0e839f8dd1e4ecef7fdc06c3f561

commit_message:
Fix replicator intersection exception when sync data to remote regions.

This patch fixed the exception (AttributeError: 'list' object has no
attribute 'intersection') when replicator try to sync data from
handoff to primary partition in more than one remote region.

Change-Id: I565c45dda8c99d36e24dbf1145f2d2527d593ac0
Closes-Bug: 1503152

commit_message:
Remove lazy-loading property compute_task_api from compute api

With conductor manager no longer calling into compute api, there is no
circular dependency between the two and because of this lazy-loading
of compute_task_api is no longer needed.

Change-Id: Ida000b5e6574bae74fa669dd72301323ad4ed9d5

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-09-23 08:57:11.000000000', 'message': 'Make more assertions in client unit tests

Some tests rely on the fake connection checking expected request
parameters, but that assumes that the fake ocnnection is even called,
which is not being checked. Add more explicit assertions that requests
are in fact made.

Change-Id: Id1c48235d7d97fd1b0feec6c19ed59a87bebdf89
'}]
commit_message:
Make more assertions in client unit tests

Some tests rely on the fake connection checking expected request
parameters, but that assumes that the fake ocnnection is even called,
which is not being checked. Add more explicit assertions that requests
are in fact made.

Change-Id: Id1c48235d7d97fd1b0feec6c19ed59a87bebdf89

[{'created': '2015-10-07 19:59:47.000000000', 'message': 'Fix ring device checks in probetests

If a device has been removed from one of the rings, it actually is set as None
within the ring. In that case the length of the devices is not True without
filtering the None devices. However, if the length matched the condition but
included a removed device the probetests would fail with a TypeError.

This fix could be done also in swift/common/ring/ring.py, but it seems it only
affects probetests right now, thus fixing it there and not changing the current
behavior.

Change-Id: I8ccf9b32a51957e040dd370bc9f711d4328d17b1
'}]
commit_message:
Fix ring device checks in probetests

If a device has been removed from one of the rings, it actually is set as None
within the ring. In that case the length of the devices is not True without
filtering the None devices. However, if the length matched the condition but
included a removed device the probetests would fail with a TypeError.

This fix could be done also in swift/common/ring/ring.py, but it seems it only
affects probetests right now, thus fixing it there and not changing the current
behavior.

Change-Id: I8ccf9b32a51957e040dd370bc9f711d4328d17b1

commit_message:
Improve resource cleanup in API v2 tests

LBaaS API v2 tests don't add cleanup right after resources are created,
they attempt to remove them at the end of the tests. In light of heavy
usage of class-level resources failure of any test leads to an
avalanche.

This change modifies API v2 tests to add clean-ups on resource
creation.

Change-Id: I1513690ff35210eaf1de7aef9db23bd69ff486e5
Closes-Bug: #1498447

commit_message:
Sort keys in table output in print_dict

We should sort the keys on the print_dict output because (1)
it's prettier and (2) it makes the output deterministic so we
can reliably test it.

Change-Id: Ifaecb249a11705ce38516642469653f091463c7a

commit_message:
Fix order of arguments in assertEqual

Some tests used incorrect order assertEqual(observed, expected).

The correct order expected by testtools is
assertEqual(expected, observed).

This patch fix the issue in the module zaqar/tests/functional/wsgi/v1_1/.
Partial-Bug: #1259292

Change-Id: I192084e8556059efda9c34b802b86435fa3c1869

commit_message:
Fix order of arguments in assertEqual


Some tests used incorrect order assertEqual(observed, expected).

The correct order expected by testtools is
assertEqual(expected, observed).

This patch fix the issue in the module zaqar/tests/unit/common/storage/ .
Patches is generated module wise to ease the review process.
Partial-Bug: #1259292

Change-Id: I40a6349dc008ea0cb4c94714f01418acdf75e3b8

commit_message:
Fix order of arguments in assertEqual

Some tests used incorrect order assertEqual(observed, expected).

The correct order expected by testtools is
assertEqual(expected, observed).

This patch fix the issue in the modules zaqar/tests/unit/storage/
and zaqar/tests/unit/notification/ modules.
Partial-Bug: #1259292

Change-Id: Iac8987782d6a21a28a0503ea7cd4ec85622f7996

commit_message:
Including link to dev docs for SLO support

SLO support is documented in the swift dev docs
but this is currently unreferenced in the config
docs. The info update required in this bug is
relevant to openstack-manuals but should be documented
in swift dev docs.

Change-Id: Ibb8030973a3f6f69392aba4a085d40000839f8b7
Closes-bug: #1499152

commit_message:
Fix order of arguments in assertEqual

Some tests used incorrect order assertEqual(observed, expected).

The correct order expected by testtools is
assertEqual(expected, observed).

This patch fix the issue in the module zaqar/tests/unit/transport/websocket .
Partial-Bug: #1259292

Change-Id: Id480e0fe6504f6511707e6fc2edfbb5e6fc219f4

commit_message:
Fix order of arguments in assertEqual

Some tests used incorrect order assertEqual(observed, expected).

The correct order expected by testtools is
assertEqual(expected, observed).

This patch fix the issue in the module zaqar/tests/unit/transport/wsgi/v1/ .
Partial-Bug: #1259292

Change-Id: I4e2252efd810ab658c1d3ad03081c3807daebfcb

[{'created': '2015-10-03 23:09:37.000000000', 'message': 'novaclient.v1_1: replace MovedModule with pep302 finder/loader

The current MovedModule implementation causes the interpreter to create
multiple objects for the same source because the each module is loaded
twice: once for the novaclient.v2 name, and again for novaclient.v1_1
name.

One negative effect of this is that multiple non-equivalent types are
created for the same class definition, depending on the import used.

This replaces MovedModule with a pep302 finder and loader, which will
return the same v2 module instance for arbitrary v1_1 names.

Closes-Bug: #1502522

commit_message:
novaclient.v1_1: replace MovedModule with pep302 finder/loader

The current MovedModule implementation causes the interpreter to create
multiple objects for the same source because the each module is loaded
twice: once for the novaclient.v2 name, and again for novaclient.v1_1
name.

One negative effect of this is that multiple non-equivalent types are
created for the same class definition, depending on the import used.

This replaces MovedModule with a pep302 finder and loader, which will
return the same v2 module instance for arbitrary v1_1 names.

Closes-Bug: #1502522
Change-Id: Ife88c163cca1e9544aa8f26549f188ca497177a6

commit_message:
Creating new user does not require project

When creating a new user, adding the user to a project is optional.
The REST api needs to respect this.

Change-Id: I2345476afcb3e0df27e50dabf5d19ec2b0f4b1dc
